 boss).\r\n\r\nWhile I am still not convinced that the WiiU is a legitimate console, it will have Batman: Arkham City Armored Edition as an exclusive. Scribblenauts. Lego City. Just Dance. ZombiU. There were a bunch of things that didn’t really matter that launched on the 3DS. However, the WiiU will be getting MassEffect 3.\r\n\r\nFor all intents and purposes, that was the end of E3. The third day had a lot of really cool games, but the coolest and best were showcased in the first couple days. However, there are really two games that stole the show and I look forward to the most: Dishonored and <del>Border</del>Dubsteplands 2. (P.S. Yes I realize there wasn''t much of a presence of Dishonored at E3, don''t whine).\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/IyDvT7XpaBc\r\n\r\nDishonored looks amazing. That’s really all I can say and link you to the trailer. The new Borderlands 2 trailer was awesome and I look forward to more guns and wubwub. Also, the new character called Zer0 looks to be an awesome update to Mordecai. Also, before you ask, the epic build up music is Nero''s Doomsday.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/kKVf5feSMEg\r\n\r\nSource: <a href="http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/09/e3-2012-in-15-minutes"><strong><em>IGN</em></strong></a>', 'The Past Two Weeks: E3 & WWDC [E3 Edition]', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '80-revision-10', '', '', '2012-06-15 03:01:48', '2012-06-15 03:01:48', '', 80, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/91/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(92, 2, '2012-06-14 23:00:20', '2012-06-15 04:00:20', '<img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-88" title="WWDC &amp; E3" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-E3-WWDC-1024x455.png" alt="" width="1024" height="455" />\r\n\r\nThe past two weeks have been rather eventful in the tech world, what with Apple’s annual World Wide Developer Conference (WWDC), the Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3), and Computex (which I will not be covering  in this article). WWDC will receive more coverage  though it is substantially shorter and less important. I care a lot more about computers than I do games (though I do enjoy the latter).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nApple holds WWDC every year as an opportunity for its developer-base to get access to new APIs and facetime, no pun intended, with Apple employees and engineers who can better answer their questions. But really, for the consumer, all it amounts to is the keynote presentation given at the beginning. This is where Apple unveils any summer merchandise or big software updates. This year was particularly eventful.  If you have yet to see it or know what happened (and you care enough to watch almost two hours of Apple congratulating itself) you can watch it <a href="http://events.apple.com.edgesuite.net/126pihbedvcoihbefvbhjkbvsefbg/event/index.html">here</a>.  For those of you who have an attention span just long enough for the good parts, head on over to <a href="http://www.macrumorslive.com/archive/wwdc12/">macrumorslive.com</a> for a very brief textual overview. When you''re done head back over here.\r\n\r\n<strong>WWDC</strong>\r\n\r\nI’m not about to get all weepy and bring up Steve Jobs, but I do kind of feel that I must point out that this was the first WWDC hosted by Tim Cook. Now, while I am not such a fan of his voice/accent/shindig, I do think that his presentation went well and that he is growing on me.\r\n\r\niOS\r\n\r\nWhat iOS 6 brought made me happy.  It was almost too lame not to be followed by a hardware redesign of the iPhone in the fall. This update focused more on actually <em>updating</em> than previous releases.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>They finally renovated the phone app: something that hasn''t been touched since god-knows when.</li>\r\n	<li>Siri “learned” a lot in her time behind Cupertino’s curtains. She/it (confusing, and hard not to dub the pronoun for Siri to be “shit”) now can tell you almost anything you could possibly need to know about American sports and some other international ones.</li>\r\n	<li>Siri also expanded her vocabulary to tons of new languages and countries. She/it can finally launch apps!</li>\r\n	<li>Apple renovated the Maps app: replacing the Google Maps service used in every update before with their own fantastically awesome service.</li>\r\n	<li>Forstall introduced turn-by-turn directions, “Flyover” and a bunch of other awesome features.</li>\r\n	<li>It feels like the entire world was mapped in 3D just so you can play around and “fly” over the Atlantic and check out the front door of your hotel before you get there.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis update also focused on integration.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Facebook got a lot of nice incorporation. Sidenote: I thought it was bizarre that Twitter got integrated in iOS5 rather than Facebook, but it must have had something to do with corporate-level witchery.</li>\r\n	<li>You can now tweet and post to Facebook via Notification Center.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Passbook is possibly one of the coolest things they introduced</strong>. In a Google Wallet-esque move, Apple created Passbook to unite all of your:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>tickets</li>\r\n	<li>boarding passes</li>\r\n	<li>cards</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nin one place. So now, instead of worrying about losing your Starbucks gift card or fumbling for the app, it launches itself when you walk inside of a Starbucks. You''re good to go right away. The future ladies and gentlemen: you can get your frappuccino even faster.\r\n\r\nLots and lots of compatibility updates for China, not just language-wise, but also things like adding Baidu as a search engine option in mobile Safari.\r\n\r\nOverall, a pretty decent update. I do feel that they had to hide a lot of features so as not to give away any plans for hardware configurations in the next iPhone.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/osx/">Mountain Lion</a>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>I don’t even really feel like going over this lame excuse for the next installment in the OS X family. Basically they ported all of the apps from iOS 5: Notification Center, reminders, notes, iMessages, iCloud, GameCenter and more, and integrated them into Lion with some of the existing system apps. Most of the updates you see in iOS 6, came to Lion: Chinese language and country optimization, documents-in-the-cloud, etc.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-96" title="Mountain Lion Default Wallpaper" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Mountain-Lion-Default-1024x640.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="640" />\r\n\r\nOh and how could I forget the pure <em>eviltude</em> of Gatekeeper? Even the name sounds terribly ominous. It basically is a form of anti-virus or security, but its default is to not allow application downloads from external sources, so only from the Mac App Store. You have the option to uncheck a box and download from external sources, but its existence just makes me think that in a future OS release, possibly even OS X 10.9, it will not just be default, but permanent.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Sidenote: Apple,  (<a href="http://www.xkcd.com/1056/">XKCD</a> obviously concurs), please name 10.9 Sabretooth or Smilodon. It is an awesome name and you have screwed yourself by naming 10.5 the best cat of them all: tiger.</li>\r\n	<li>Sidenote 2: Naming OSs after cats is really dumb, I hope you realize this now. Furthermore, the default Snow Leopard and Leopard wallpapers were pretty cool, but Lion''s was awesome. I think that Mountain Lion''s default wallpaper may be the only good thing about it.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/mac/">Mac Refresh</a>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-95" title="MBP Retina Side" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png" alt="" width="310" height="131" /></a>This is the real good stuff. The MacBook Pro line of the Mac family hasn’t seen a hardware redesign in a while, yet in a way it still hasn’t. Apple silently dropped the 17” MacBook Pro, which I’m sure some are sad to see go, but they wouldn’t have dropped it unless it was still popular. For the 13” and 15” MBPs, all they got was an internal refresh: awesome powerhouse Intel Ivy Bridges. The 15” variety got Nvidia GPUs, but nevertheless, it was a rather uneventful update for those poor guys. The same goes for the MacBook Air, the 11” and 13” varieties received nearly identical updates with new and more powerful Intel processors, more RAM, and increased standard SSD capacity. No body got a better or higher definition screen. Even in the conference center you could tell people were a bit disappointed that nothing was truly changed. Then Mr. Schiller said “So what’s next…” Thats when you knew it was coming. He proceeded to introduce an awesome new MacBook Pro variety. It is about a fifth as thin as the older 15”. It now sports a gorgeous Retina display which has more than twice the pixels of an HDTV. 2880 x 1800 at 220 ppi for a total of 5,184,000 pixels, a.k.a. more than anyone with only two eyeballs needs. <a href="http://www.apple.com/macbook-pro/specs/">For all of you spec-heads.</a> It has a massive battery, an HDMI port, two Thunderbolt ports, and… two USB 3.0 ports (the SD MacBook Pros got the USB 3.0 as well). The headphone and microphone jacks were unified into one and Apple introduced a “MagSafe 2” power connection. They even took the time to design special fans with a-symmetrical blade arrangements so the laptop is quieter. This all translates into one bad ass laptop that has skyrocketed to the top of my to-do list.\r\n\r\nWWDC and E3 were pretty awesome, but that’s about all that happened in the past two weeks, though I am pretty positive I missed something somewhere.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSource: <a href="http://www.macrumorslive.com/archive/wwdc12/"><strong><em>MacRumorsLive</em></strong></a>', 'The Past Two Weeks: E3 & WWDC [WWDC Edition]', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-past-two-weeks-e3-wwdc-wwdc-edition', '', '', '2012-06-15 00:29:40', '2012-06-15 05:29:40', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=92', 0, 'post', '', 0),
