du as a search engine option in mobile Safari.\n\nOverall, a pretty decent update. I do feel that they had to hide a lot of features so as not to give away any plans for hardware configurations in the next iPhone.\n\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/osx/">Mountain Lion</a>\n\n<strong> </strong>I don’t even really feel like going over this lame excuse for the next installment in the OS X family. Basically they ported all of the apps from iOS 5: Notification Center, reminders, notes, iMessages, iCloud, GameCenter and more, and integrated them into Lion with some of the existing system apps. Most of the updates you see in iOS 6, came to Lion: Chinese language and country optimization, documents-in-the-cloud, etc.\n\n<img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-96" title="Mountain Lion Default Wallpaper" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Mountain-Lion-Default-1024x640.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="640" />\n\nOh and how could I forget the pure <em>eviltude</em> of Gatekeeper? Even the name sounds terribly ominous. It basically is a form of anti-virus or security, but its default is to not allow application downloads from external sources, so only from the Mac App Store. You have the option to uncheck a box and download from external sources, but its existence just makes me think that in a future OS release, possibly even OS X 10.9, it will not just be default, but permanent.\n<ul>\n	<li>Sidenote: Apple,  (<a href="http://www.xkcd.com/1056/">XKCD</a> obviously concurs), please name 10.9 Sabretooth or Smilodon. It is an awesome name and you have screwed yourself by naming 10.5 the best cat of them all: tiger.</li>\n	<li>Sidenote 2: Naming OSs after cats is really dumb, I hope you realize this now. Furthermore, the default Snow Leopard and Leopard wallpapers were pretty cool, but Lion''s was awesome. I think that Mountain Lion''s default wallpaper may be the only good thing about it.</li>\n</ul>\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/mac/">Mac Refresh</a>\n\n<strong> </strong><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-95" title="MBP Retina Side" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png" alt="" width="310" height="131" /></a>This is the real good stuff. The MacBook Pro line of the Mac family hasn’t seen a hardware redesign in a while, yet in a way it still hasn’t. Apple silently dropped the 17” MacBook Pro, which I’m sure some are sad to see go, but they wouldn’t have dropped it unless it was still popular. For the 13” and 15” MBPs, all they got was an internal refresh: awesome powerhouse Intel Ivy Bridges. The 15” variety got Nvidia GPUs, but nevertheless, it was a rather uneventful update for those poor guys. The same goes for the MacBook Air, the 11” and 13” varieties received nearly identical updates with new and more powerful Intel processors, more RAM, and increased standard SSD capacity. No body got a better or higher definition screen. Even in the conference center you could tell people were a bit disappointed that nothing was truly changed. Then Mr. Schiller said “So what’s next…” Thats when you knew it was coming. He proceeded to introduce an awesome new MacBook Pro variety. It is about a fifth as thin as the older 15”. It now sports a gorgeous Retina display which has more than twice the pixels of an HDTV. 2880 x 1800 at 220 ppi for a total of 5,184,000 pixels, a.k.a. more than anyone with only two eyeballs needs. <a href="http://www.apple.com/macbook-pro/specs/">For all of you spec-heads.</a> It has a massive battery, an HDMI port, two Thunderbolt ports, and… two USB 3.0 ports (the SD MacBook Pros got the USB 3.0 as well). The headphone and microphone jacks were unified into one and Apple introduced a “MagSafe 2” power connection. They even took the time to design special fans with a-symmetrical blade arrangements so the laptop is quieter. This all translates into one bad ass laptop 