e a lot of features so as not to give away any plans for hardware configurations in the next iPhone.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/osx/">Mountain Lion</a>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>I don’t even really feel like going over this lame excuse for the next installment in the OS X family. Basically they ported all of the apps from iOS 5: Notification Center, reminders, notes, iMessages, iCloud, GameCenter and more, and integrated them into Lion with some of the existing system apps. Most of the updates you see in iOS 6, came to Lion: Chinese language and country optimization, documents-in-the-cloud, etc.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-96" title="Mountain Lion Default Wallpaper" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Mountain-Lion-Default-1024x640.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="640" />\r\n\r\nOh and how could I forget the pure eviltude of Gatekeeper? Event he name sounds terribly ominous. It basically is a form of anti-virus or security, but its default is to not allow application downloads from external sources, so only from the Mac App Store. You have the option to uncheck a box and download from external sources, but its existence just makes me think that in a future OS release, possibly even OS X 10.9, it will not just be default, but permanent. Sidenote: Apple, as <a href="http://www.xkcd.com/1056/">XKCD</a> obviously concurs, please name 10.9 Sabretooth or Smilodon. It is an awesome name and you have screwed yourself by naming 10.5 the best cat of them all: tiger. Sidenote2: Naming OSs after cats is really dumb, I hope you realize this now. Furthermore, the default Snow Leopard and Leopar wallpapers were pretty cool, but Lion''s was awesome. I think that Mountain Lion''s default wallpaper may be the only good thing about it.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.apple.com/mac/">Mac Refresh</a>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-95" title="MBP Retina Side" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-MBP-Retina-Side.png" alt="" width="310" height="131" /></a>This is the real good stuff. The MacBook Pro line of the Mac family hasn’t seen a hardware redesign in a while, yet in a way it still hasn’t. Apple silently dropped the 17” MacBook Pro, which I’m sure some are sad to see go, but they wouldn’t have dropped it unless it was still popular. However, as for the 13” and 15” MBPs, all they got was an internal refresh: awesome powerhouse Intel Ivy Bridges. The 15” variety got Nvidia GPUs, but nevertheless, it was a rather uneventful update for those poor guys. The same goes for the MacBook Air, the 11” and 13” varieties received nearly identical updates with new and more powerful Intel processors, more RAM, and increased standard SSD capacity. No body got a better or higher definition screen. Even in the conference center you could tell people were a bit disappointed that nothing was truly changed. However, then Mr. Schiller said “So what’s next…” Thats when you knew it was coming. He proceeded to introduce an awesome new MacBook Pro variety. It is about a fifth as thin as the older 15”. It now sports a gorgeous Retina display which has more than twice the pixels of an HDTV. 2880 x 1800 at 220 ppi for a total of 5,184,000 pixels, a.k.a. more than anyone with only two eyeballs needs. <a href="http://www.apple.com/macbook-pro/specs/">For all of you spec-heads.</a> It has a massive battery, an HDMI port, two Thunderbolt ports, and… two USB 3.0 ports (the SD MacBook Pros got the USB 3.0 as well). The headphone and microphone jacks were unified into one and Apple introduced a “MagSafe 2” power connection. They even took the time to design special fans with a-symmetrical blade arrangements so the laptop is quieter. This all translates into one bad ass laptop that has skyrocketed to the top of my to-do list.\r\n\r\nWWDC and E3 were pretty awesome, but that’s about all that happened in the past two weeks, though I am pretty positive I missed something somewhere.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSource: <a href="http://www.macrumorslive.com/archive/wwdc12/"><strong><em>MacRumorsLive</em></strong></a>', 'The Past Two Weeks: E3 & WWDC [WWDC Edition]', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '92-revision-13', '', '', '2012-06-14 23:09:42', '2012-06-15 04:09:42', '', 92, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/114/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(115, 2, '2012-06-15 03:02:00', '2012-06-15 03:02:00', '<img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-88" title="WWDC &amp; E3" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-14-E3-WWDC-1024x455.png" alt="" width="1024" height="455" />\r\n\r\nThe past two weeks have been rather eventful in the tech world, what with Apple’s annual World Wide Developer Conference (WWDC), the Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3) and Computex, which I will not be covering that in this article. However, I must confess that WWDC will, while it is substantially shorter and less important, be covered a little more thoroughly as I care a lot more about computers than I do games, however I do enjoy the latter.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nE3 is hosted by the Entertainment Software Association annually as a trade show for the computer and video games industries. Usually this conference is held in the Los Angeles Convention Center, but in 2007 and 2008 they tried screwing around with some things that didn’t work out too well for them so they reverted back to the norm. E3 is composed of a general-admissions-kind-of-deal in its main hall in which there are a ton of open booths set up by the various companies and organizations to attract the passerby along with big press conferences at some "booths." There are also smaller private rooms off to the side that are usually invitation only.\r\n\r\n<strong>E3</strong>\r\n\r\nFor such a large conference, I’m going to do my best to cover this chronologically, however I’m not promising anything. And just to warn everyone, I am an XBox man, but my allegiances don’t lie entirely swayed to that corner. Also, I will probably miss a lot: no whining.\r\n\r\nAt Microsoft’s press conference a new Halo 4 trailer was shown off along with some new gameplay. Personally, AWESOME. Virtually everybody seems to be complaining that it is losing what it had in the beginning and entirely deviating. Well yes,  a different studio is taking over production duties so I would expect it to change, but beyond that, I am all for change if 343 can make an awesome new game. It was also announced that Halo 4 would be the start of a new trilogy and that the enemies would not be mainly Covenant or Flood. Ubisoft showed off the kick ass Splinter Cell: Black List. Then EA showed off sports games. Now let me take a second here to note that I have never understood these. I hate sports games. They not only seem entirely pointless, boring, and unrealistic, but why not just kick a ball around irl? Regardless, EA unveiled Madden and FIFA ’13. Trailers were also aired for the new Fable, a stupid installment in an already dead series: Gears: Judgement, what looks to be an awesome racing game - Forza: Horizon, Nike+Kinect (again, who cares?), South Park, and awesome game called Matter, Ascension, Tomb Raider, Resident Evil 6, COD: Black Ops 2, and tons more. They also announced a lot of things for the XBox Live experience in general, mainly revolving around broadcast sports and cable TV partnerships. Music was touched upon, but not really discussed. However, SmartGlass looks pretty awesome and like a far superior idea to the WiiU’s take. SmartGlass allows the user to download an app on their smartphone or tablet, currently only on Windows Marketplace and hopefully coming to iOS or Android, and have this work either as a remote for the XBox or as an extension of the game itself, much as the WiiU’s GamePad does.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/5N-CRrP9xjQ\r\n\r\nSony’s conference launched with a trailer for Beyond Two Souls. This looks stunningly awesome, sadly I don’t own a PS3 so I won’t be getting a taste of this on my own. Sony announced a PSVita version of AllStars Battle Royale with support for cross-platform gaming and a COD title for it called Black Ops: Declassified. A special version of Assassin’s Creed III was announced for the PSVita as well. Wonderbook with AR looked pretty stupid. It’s basically a book with a ton of QR codes and motion tracked points so games and “stories” can come to life. However, there will be a Harry Potter launch title for it. God of War: Ascension was announced for a spring 2013 release. Sony wrapped up with an awesome demo of The Last of Us.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/ZJmjXBXn9zY\r\n\r\nLater on, EA showed off an awesome looking DeadSpace 3 and expansions for BattleField 3. I was and am confused by a third installment in DeadSpace this as I thought he died at the end of DS2? Alas. I assume they will work in some sort of lame resurrection story. Need For Speed: Most Wanted was announced, EA got the rights to UFC and there will be new DLCs for Star Wars: The Old Republic.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/83qSiBcA7Yg\r\n\r\nUbisoft was the unexpected sucker punch. They showed off a ton of WiiU games such as Rayman Legends, Rabbids Land and a couple others.Nearly everything else compares to an awesome new game that came from nowhere: Watchdogs. This combines all awesome things: hackers, assassins, guns, and awesomeness.\r\n\r\nNintendo intro’ed their next console: the WiiU. Their showed off the “Pro Controller” which is basically an XBox 360 controller for the WiiU: this would be for those of us who would prefer not to have a large screen below us, like one huge DS. They also said that the tablet controller, dubbed the GamePad, would have dual analog sticks along with onboard NFC and a way to act as a standard TV remote. Nintendo’s conference seemed rather… meh to me. They showcased a new game and announced that the WiiU will now be able to support two GamePads (the things with the touch screens). MiiVerse was announced as a WiiU-centric social network where people can send texts, hand written notes, see each other’s miis and much more. Eventually access to this will expand to the DS, smartphones and computers. Super Mario Bros U was announced, but, again, looks rather meh with some social networking built in. In a collection like game, there were hints at Samus getting a chance at the WiiU (which would be boss).\r\n\r\nWhile I am still not convinced that the WiiU is a legitimate console, it will have Batman: Arkham City Armored Edition as an exclusive. Scribblenauts. Lego City. Just Dance. ZombiU. There were a bunch of things that didn’t really matter that launched on the 3DS. However, the WiiU will be getting MassEffect 3.\r\n\r\nFor all intents and purposes, that was the end of E3. The third day had a lot of really cool games, but the coolest and best were showcased in the first couple days. However, there are really two games that stole the show and I look forward to the most: Dishonored and <del>Border</del>Dubsteplands 2. (P.S. Yes I realize there wasn''t much of a presence of Dishonored at E3, don''t whine).\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/IyDvT7XpaBc\r\n\r\nDishonored looks amazing. That’s really all I can say and link you to the trailer. The new Borderlands 2 trailer was awesome and I look forward to more guns and wubwub. Also, the new character called Zer0 looks to be an awesome update to Mordecai. Also, before you ask, the epic build up music is Nero''s Doomsday.\r\n\r\nhttp://youtu.be/kKVf5feSMEg\r\n\r\nSource: <a href="http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/09/e3-2012-in-15-minutes"><strong><em>IGN</em></strong></a>', 'The Past Two Weeks: E3 & WWDC [E3 Edition]', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '80-revision-11', '', '', '2012-06-15 03:02:00', '2012-06-15 03:02:00', '', 80, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/115/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
