(125, 1, '2012-06-14 23:16:28', '2012-06-15 04:16:28', 'By J. Meeks\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Riot-Police.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-118" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Riot-Police-300x197.png" alt="" width="300" height="197" /></a>\n\nAll you can hear are the protestors’ footsteps on Athenian cobblestone. They’re somewhere in the distance but watching the video online you can’t really tell how far. The police, in riot gear, shift, almost pacing. They’re perturbed. Aware of what’s coming they slap their padded gear into place and secure their gloved fists around the handles of their nightsticks. Scrutinizing them, watching them look at one another from behind glossy visors, you can only assume that the riot squad is keenly aware of their own numbers. There are about thirty of them. Now they can see the protestors. The activists’ arms are locked. They’re a sea of enraged bodies assembled in the streets and above their raised fists is a swath of billowing, red, flags. The protestors march right up to the line that the police have made in the street. The footsteps stop for a moment. The police push back against the line of activists, trying to force the protestors back down the street. Then the flags come down. Wooden poles draped in red fabric break against helmets as the protestors march forward, pushing through the line. For a moment the activists retreat. I can only suppose the police wondered why. Then, whistling through the air, the answer came to them.\n\nGreece is on fire.\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Riot-Cop-Petrol-Bomb.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-117" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Riot-Cop-Petrol-Bomb-300x196.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="196" /></a>\n\nIn November of 2011, when Greece’s first round of austerity measures was proposed, in which tremendous privatization and union dismantling was to take place, Prime Minister George Papandreou declared that he could not move forward with such a deal without a <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15549352">referendum</a>. On November 1,, Papandreou told the members of the Hellenic Parliament and his Cabinet that he would not acquiesce to such a proposal without the blessing of the people.\n\nPapandreou’s reaction was, of course, understandable. The terms of the bailout agreement were quite the bundle: a 100 billion Euro deal packaged in public spending downsizes, pension and salary lacerations, and a lowering of the minimum wage. However, within two days, on November 3, amidst international pressure, the dream of a referendum had died.\n\nOn November 11 George Papandreou had been removed from office. His replacement, <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15643454">Lucas Papademos</a>, a favorite of the “troika”, France, and Germany, backed the European Central Bank’s negotiated economic barbarisms wholeheartedly. And why shouldn’t he? He wrote them.\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Lucas-Papademos.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-119" title="Lucas Papademos" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Lucas-Papademos-300x172.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="172" /></a>\n\nA supply-side economist since his days at MIT, Lucas Papademos, one of the bankers responsible for the ruin of Greece, could never let a good crisis go to waste.\n\nMr. Papademos, a former professor, received his Ph.D. in Economics in 1977. With positions at the University of Athens, Harvard, and Columbia I suppose it was impossible for him not to network. It should come as no surprise then that when he left academia (this applies to Harvard only loosely) in the mid-1980s he took a position as the Chief Economist of the Bank of Greece and in short time became Governor of the Bank of Greece in 1994.\n\nFrom 1994 to 2002, Papademos was the administrator of the Bank of Greece. Papademos, during his tenure as the bank’s Governor, was the key figure in Greece’s changeover from the drachma to the Euro. Despite this he left Bank of Greece just a year after the currency transition was made.\n\nBut where did Papademos go?\n\n<a href="http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/e39974f6-f580-11e0-94b1-00144feab49a.html#axzz1xpq4UiJ4">Jean-Claude Trichet</a>, a member of the <a href="http://www.bis.org/press/p060626a.htm">Board of Directors for the Bank of International Settlements</a> and <a href="http://quotes.wsj.com/EADSY/company-people">The European Aeronautic Defense and Space Company</a> was President of the European Central Bank from 2003 to 2011. It was into Trichet’s “austere” arms that Papademos ran.\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Jean-Claude-Trichet.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-120" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Jean-Claude-Trichet-300x212.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="212" /></a>\n\nAs though this moment of upward mobility was not suspect enough, it becomes even more devious when Trichet’s chairmanship of the Group of 30 (concurrent with his Presidential term of the ECB) is investigated. The Group of 30, founded in 1978 (nine years before Trichet joined), was launched by the Rockefeller Foundation. Dedicated to promoting neoliberal understandings of finances and economics as interplay between private and public, the G30’s primary focus was to broaden the understanding of the roles that are played and the choices made that lead to economic disaster. Ironically enough, the Group of 30 was once home to former Federal Reserve Chairman (and diminished Ayn Rand devotee) <a href="http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1877351_1877350_1877331,00.html">Alan Greenspan</a>.\n\n<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1bX_vhojH8c">Alan Greenspan''s Apology</a>\n\nGreenspan was Time magazine’s #1 person to blame for the financial crisis. Greenspan and the G30 have a long history of deregulatory thinking paved with conflicts of interest. The Chairman of the Board of Trustees, <a href="http://www.jpmorgan.com/cm/cs?pagename=JPM_redesign/JPM_Content_C/Generic_Detail_Page_Template&amp;cid=1259886088790&amp;c=JPM_Content_C">Jacob Frenkel</a>, provides just another example.\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Jacob-Frenkel.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-121" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Jacob-Frenkel-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://faculty.citadel.edu/silver/IF/MBA_course/Chapter01.pdf">Dr. Frenkel</a>, Governor of the Bank of Israel from 1991 to 2000, is currently as the Chairman of JP Morgan Chase International. It would be ridiculous to blame Frankel for JP Morgan’s part in the international financial meltdown – he only took his position in 2009. One, could make the claim that, as the Economic Counselor and D.O.R at the International Monetary Fund, he may have done some damage. Known world-wide for keeping impoverished nations under their thumb, the IMF and its representatives have been accused of raping more than Parisian hotel maids. There’s no doubt that Jacob Frenkel promoted some of the union busting and privatization techniques currently being shoved down the Greek people’s throats. But it doesn’t end there. From 2004 to 2009, Frenkel was the Vice Chairman of AIG (of Credit Default Swap and CEO bonus fame) and before this, from 2000 to 2004, he was the Chairman of Merill Lynch. Moreover, his fellowship within <a href="http://www.econometricsociety.org/">the Econometrics society</a> an organization first directed by Irving Fisher. Fisher was once called by Milton Friedman “the greatest economist the United States has ever produced”. It is not surprising then that the Econometrics Society’s founding members are some of the biggest libertarian pioneers in human history. Joseph Schumpeter laid the foundation for Bain Capital’s business strategy of corporate gutting. Harold Hotelling influenced Milton Friedman, father of crisis capitalism and a neo-colonial pioneer. Carl Snyder, targeted the Federal Reserve as a scapegoat for the Great Depression, “Capitalism, the Creator”.\n\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Milton-Freidman.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-122" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Milton-Freidman-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>\n\nWhat’s so peculiar about the relationship between Frenkel, Trichet, Papademos, the G30, the Economics Faculty of the U of C and the members of the Econometrics Society, in addition to their ideology, conflicts of interest and their hands in the deregulation of the manipulation financial system, and its subsequent meltdown, is how, on a large scale, cronyism and neoliberal economic ideology are intertwined. Equally curious is how it relates to Greece so heavily on one hand and also plays such an obvious part in the world, on the other.\n\nWhen asked about the needs of Greece, Papademos responded, “We need supply-side measures.” Frenkel, Chairman of the Board of Trustees for the Group of 30 and colleague of Trichet (Papademos’s former employer), was the doctoral student of Robert Mundell. Professor of Economics at the University of Chicago and the founder of supply-side economics. Mundell played his part as a key theoretical founder of the Euro currency. The connections among the global economic players is alarming. Almost everyone appointed to positions of power in the global economic almost is playing Six Degrees of Separation from Gordon Gecko. The former Prime Minister of Greece, who was appointed to enforce Greece’s policy of self-immolation also sold the gas and the matches after driving the economy into the ground. Lucas’s former employer, Jean-Claude Trichet, gave Papademos the job once Papademos replaced the drachma in 2001. Trichet, while head of the international economic organization (with Jacob Frenkel as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees), actively enforced the theories of Robert Mundell. Mundell was Frenkel’s mentor.\n\nFrom the outside, <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17986065">SYRIZA</a>, the Coalition for the Radical Left, the party predicted to win Greece’s parliamentary elections on Sunday, seems bloodthirsty. The popular media have painted these leftists as childish and their leader, Alexis Tsipras, a former member of the Communist Party of Greece, as irrational for wanting to tear up the austerity agreements.\n\nWould Japan trust Oppenheimer to rebuild Hiroshima? Would we criticize them for rejecting such an offer? Would we allow George W. Bush or Ronald Reagan to force their policies on us, unelected?\n\nSYRIZA has promised to strive towards Socialism of the 21st century. <a href="http://www.workersliberty.org/story/2012/06/01/syriza-says-stop-paying-debt-nationalise-banks-under-workers-control">They want to nationalize the Greek banks</a>, reverse budget cuts and restore the minimum wage. They want to investigate and arrest the guilty bankers, like Lucas Papademos, who brought this upon their country. They want to take back the Public Power Corporation and the Hellenic Telecommunications Organization. They want to abandon NATO. They want to lower the taxes on the poor and middle class and raise them on the wealthy. They want to restore government pensions for those living in poverty. But all of this notwithstanding, SYRIZA is dedicated to staying in Euro Zone, fearing that the bailout agreement will push them out of the European currency. Though their rhetoric is blistering to some, who are we to disagree with Europe’s red phoenix which is rising from the blazing ashes of a neoliberal Greece? Particularly if they want to choke the banker’s appetite for destruction in the smoke.', '"Appetite for Destruction": The Banker Coven That Ruined Greece and Ignited the Far Left', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '102-revision', '', '', '2012-06-14 23:16:28', '2012-06-15 04:16:28', '', 102, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/125/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(142, 2, '2012-06-14 23:35:18', '2012-06-15 04:35:18', 'by X. Stewart\r\n\r\nDuring this offseason (which has been quite…an…off season) there have been many stories of note. You’ve got RG3’s legendary arm, Tebow in New York, and (just what in the world is going on with) the Saints. This aside, the story that struck me the most was a report on <strong><a href="http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8003562/jacksonville-jaguars-rookie-justin-blackmon-arrested-dui">ESPN</a>. </strong>The focus of the account was on the Jaguars’ first round draft pick, Justin Blackmon, and his arrest. Now usually things like this don’t affect me… but then I saw where he was arrested (Oklahoma). I went deeper. My mind was boggled. What did this mean? For starters, I knew Jack Del Rio was going to have to do a LOT of work to do to keep Blackmon in line…but…there was something more.\r\n\r\nThe Universe hates the Jacksonville Jaguars.\r\n\r\nJust highlighting some of the bad luck the Jaguars have had over the years I can already see another year of disappointment for Jacksonville and it’s all because of their terrible luck.\r\n\r\n<strong>Jacksonville’s Division</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I’ll admit that AFC South is no NFC East. The teams in Jacksonville’s division are far from swimming in Superbowl rings. Even so, a huge problem for the Jaguars is their division. If you’ve been paying attention for the past ten years, the Indianapolis Colts have basically run AFC South.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/colts1219.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-128" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/colts1219-300x196.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="196" /></a>\r\n\r\nEven with the Colts out of play, the Texans stepped up and showed that they could be the new top dog (even without Matt Schaub). This sets up a very predictable division structure. There usually is one good team in the AFC South, two mediocre teams, and the Jaguars. Without any real competition for division winner it makes it even harder for the Jaguars to get a playoff spot. All of this aside, one might think that they could just lose one year but get a better draft pick due to their higher position. The Jaguars’ luck isn’t even that good.\r\n\r\n<strong>Draft Picks</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>Remember Justin Blackmon from the beginning of the article?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/justin_blackmon_10-27-2010_thir82a.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-129" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/justin_blackmon_10-27-2010_thir82a-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>\r\n\r\nWell he’s simply the latest in a string of high drafted receivers selected by Jacksonville. For some reason, all of the seemingly good choices the Jaguars make inevitably turn against them. Don’t get me wrong, drafting wide receivers is a good choice, but when you’re the Jaguars for some reason it is probably the worst decision you could possibly make. Of the three previous wide receivers the Jaguars have selected, in the first round, none of them are even on the team anymore (the average amount of time the three receivers have been with the Jaguars is a little over four years). That means that the receivers the Jaguars draft don’t even get to receive all the money from their rookie contract before they get cut, arrested, or shipped off to Canada. What makes this even worse is that their horrible draft picks aren''t limited to just receivers. Derrick Harvey is a bust of recent memory whose situation can easily be chalked up to bad luck.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Derrick_Harvey.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-131" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Derrick_Harvey-158x300.jpg" alt="" width="158" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nAfter having the Jaguars trade FOUR draft picks for him, he came into the league and had an adequate rookie year. But, like most college players, Harvey was used to a certain position and when that position changed it impacted his stats heavily. Many first, second, and third rounders in recent memory were all seemingly good picks; Blaine Abbert, Jarrett Dillard, and Quentin Groves – now they’re all contestants for biggest bust in the Jaguars’ tragedy. All in all the draft isn’t too good to Jacksonville.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Panthers as a Measuring Stick</strong>\r\n\r\nIn 1995 two expansion teams were added into the NFL. By now you should know them. One of them was the Jacksonville Jaguars; the other, the Carolina Panthers. Now, I’m not saying the Panthers are perfect but at least when they’re down they go down enough to get a number one draft pick. Now they have Cam Newton and Luke Kuechly. Even before all this the Panthers had an appearance in a Superbowl! Not only that, but, the Panthers operate in a much tougher division with the Falcons, Saints, and the Buccaneers.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/107342976_10.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-132" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/107342976_10-300x285.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="285" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Fan Support</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Jaguars suck-ness notwithstanding, look at the market the Jaguars have to work with. Even with an 800,000 person fan base, the new owner, Shahid Khan, practically begs fans to buy season tickets. Jacksonville won’t even help itself. Yet, Green Bay, with its miniscule population, has season tickets sold out every year. One explanation for this is the oversaturation of NFL teams in Florida. The Dolphins, the Buccaneers, and the Jaguars must all fight it out for the state’s attention. This might explain why all three teams aren’t doing so well. The Jaguars cannot distinguish themselves. Try finding a Jaguars game on television. I dare you.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/otkwiml127.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-133" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/otkwiml127-300x213.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="213" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>The Coaching Staff</strong>\r\n\r\nThis last point is another great example of exactly why the Universe hates the Jaguars. Even when things go well the Management is awful. Take last year for example: David Garrard was coming off of a decent year as quarterback. Hell, at the time it seemed he was poised to take the Jaguars to the playoffs (he even got a Pro Bowl out of it). What does Del Rio do? He cuts Garrard in favor of freshly drafted Blaine Gabbert. Fast forward to this season: there are fans already calling for Gabbert’s head. Maurice Jones Drew is the absolute soul of that team, and I have a feeling that it might be time for him to take his talents elsewhere. Even if he wants to stay it seems likely that the Jaguars’ luck will mess it up.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/jags-jdr-sad.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-135" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/jags-jdr-sad-300x217.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="217" /></a>', 'The Universe Hates the Jacksonville Jaguars', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '127-revision-4', '', '', '2012-06-14 23:35:18', '2012-06-15 04:35:18', '', 127, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/142/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
