(173, 14, '2012-06-15 01:53:25', '2012-06-15 06:53:25', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\nSo when learning a programming language, it is often customary to start out with a simple program that print''s the words "Hello, world!". In some languages this actually takes a couple lines (like C, C++, Java, etc.); in Python though, it takes only one. Fire up IDLE (which stands for <strong>I</strong>ntegrated <strong>D</strong>eve<strong>l</strong>opment <strong>E</strong>nvironment, why they didn''t call it an IDE like everyone else, I have no idea) or your terminal or if know how to use it. Just so you know, everything that you should type into your Python shell will be written like so:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;You type me into your Python shell!</pre>\n<pre>Your Python shell returns this!</pre>\nJust like your IDLE. Any outputs of scripts will appear without three carrots. Anyway, type the following into your IDLE:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;print("Hello, world!")</pre>\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\nCongratulations, you just wrote your first Python program! If you were to want you were to want to save it as a file, all you would have to do would be Control/Command-N, type that line in, and then save it as whatever.py', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision', '', '', '2012-06-15 01:53:25', '2012-06-15 06:53:25', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/173/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
