(180, 14, '2012-06-15 05:42:19', '2012-06-15 10:42:19', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\nNote: When I say "shell", "Python shell",  or "interpreter", I mean the window that pops up when you first open IDLE, that takes python lines, and executes them.\n\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, what is a variable? Well it''s kind of like a container, but more like "tentacle" grasping a value, or no value at at all. Let me give an example, I would suggest entering this into your Python shell to start seeing how the language works. Also just try out a couple things to see if they work, messing around is a great way to explore a language.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\nWhen that line is executed by your interpreter, the variable x is "grasping" the string "Hello, world!". A string is a series of characters, grouped together into a single value. In Python, strings are represented by characters between a set of  single ('') or double (") quotes. This means that\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = ''Hello, world!''</pre>\nassigns x to the exact same value. One way to find out the value of a variable is to simply enter it into the shell, for example\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\noutputs\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\nOkay, simple, right? A string isn''t the only type of value that a variable can "grasp". Another  is an integer. Integers are just like they sound, numbers that are round (ie. 1, 2, 3) and can be positive or negative\n<pre></pre>', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-7', '', '', '2012-06-15 05:42:19', '2012-06-15 10:42:19', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/180/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(175, 14, '2012-06-15 02:15:43', '2012-06-15 07:15:43', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\nSo when learning a programming language, it is often customary to start out with a simple program that print''s the words "Hello, world!". In some languages this actually takes a couple lines (like C, C++, Java, etc.); in Python though, it takes only one. Fire up IDLE (which stands for <strong>I</strong>ntegrated <strong>D</strong>eve<strong>l</strong>opment <strong>E</strong>nvironment, why they didn''t call it an IDE like everyone else, I have no idea) or your terminal or if know how to use it. Just so you know, everything that you should type into your Python shell will be written like so:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; You type me into your Python shell!</pre>\n<pre>Your Python shell returns this!</pre>\nJust like your IDLE. Any outputs of scripts will appear without three carrots. Anyway, type the following into your IDLE:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print("Hello, world!")</pre>\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\nCongratulations, you just wrote your first Python program! If you were to want to save the script as a file, all you would have to do would be Control/Command-N, type that line in, and then save it as "myFirstProgram.py". When you double click that file, it should open in the Python shell (either the IDLE or your terminal), where you can run it again. Now, let me explain exactly what happened. First of all, "Hello, world" is what is called a string; just several characters grouped together. In Python, strings can either be shown with double (") or single ('') quotes around them, so the following would also print "Hello, world!":\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(''Hello, world'')</pre>\nOne thing you may notice is the following:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; "Hello, world"</pre>\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\nThis is not actually a good way of printing things, since when running that same line from a file, nothing would show up. That kind of printing is only useful if you are in a shell, running code line by line. Even then, I would highly suggest using print to display text just to make it into a habit. Now, lets mix things up a bit. Try typing the following into your shell:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\nThe shell should then return the following:\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\nWhat you just did, was store the string "Hello, world!" in variable x. Then, when you entered x, it printed that variable to the shell.  All that happened, was that when the shell saw that x wasn''t surrounded by quotes and that it was an assigned variable, it just replaced x with the value assigned to it, the string "Hello, world". So, when you enter\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(x)</pre>\nThe shell replaces x with the string "Hello, world" and returns\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\nAll the shell did was replace x with what you assigned it to be! Now, let me explain what "print" is. "print" is a function; a function is a group of code that is run, with different values being passed to it. The values passed to a function are enclosed in parenthesis after the function, and seperated by commas if there are multiple values.', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-3', '', '', '2012-06-15 02:15:43', '2012-06-15 07:15:43', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/175/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
