(187, 14, '2012-06-15 06:23:53', '2012-06-15 11:23:53', '<h2><strong>Why you should want to learn Python (or any programming language)</strong></h2>\r\n<em>If you don''t need to be convinced, and just want to start learning the language, I''d suggest just skipping to the next section. If you already know a programing langage, especially if it''s an object oriented one, you can probably just skip or skim the first three or four lessons.</em>\r\n\r\nComputers are a huge part of our daily lives, and are pretty important to the workings of the modern world. It would make sense to know how about the inner workings of one, right? What programming allows you to do with computers is incredibly useful and it allows you to use a computers raw power to do exactly what you want. Instead of having to search around for software that does what you want (or even worse do it by hand), you can just write some code that does the job for you. By learning a language, many opportunities open up for you, you can eventually work on making games, or even turn the skill into a profession. Python itself is a great starting language; it has a simple syntax and a gentle learning curve, yet can also be very powerful. After these couple of tutorials, you should be able to start making scripts that are actually useful for you in the real world. Anyway, lets get started!\r\n<h2>Installing Python</h2>\r\nMost computers do not have Python installed when you first get them (only Macs that I know of, and that''s Python 2 .7, which is not what we''ll be using for this), so you''ll have to install it. There are many ways to do this, so I''ll go through a couple. All of it should be fairly simple once you download the file, since it contains a helpful readme.\r\n\r\nFirst, go to Python''s <a title="Python download" href="http://www.python.org/download/">download page</a> and click on the 3.x version for you operating system (currently 3.2.3). Once downloaded, just doubled click the package, and follow the instructions. For Mac and Windows machines, this will be a simple installer like most programs. For Linux, it''s a compressed file that you should unzip and then just follow the readme (but if your running Linux in the first place, you''ll know what to do).\r\n\r\nNote: If you are unsure about whether your computer is 32 or 64 bit, follow these instructions (even though it''s probably 64 bit unless it''s fairly old). Additionally, if you have a package manager installed like homebrew or macports, you can most likely just use that to install Python, just make sure your downloading "python3". You also won''t get the GUI if you use these, but that''s honestly not that bad, the terminal version works just as well, if not better.\r\n<h4>Mac</h4>\r\nGo The Apple <strong>Icon-&gt;About This Mac </strong>and look at your version. If it''s 10.6 or above, go with the 64 bit, otherwise the 32 bit.\r\n<h4>Windows</h4>\r\nOpen System by clicking the Start button <img title="Picture of the Start button" src="http://res2.windows.microsoft.com/resbox/en/Windows%20Vista/main/4f6cbd09-148c-4dd8-b1f2-48f232a2fd33_47.png" alt="Picture of the Start button" width="15" height="15" data-id="pageContainer0_ID0EUE" />, clicking Control Panel, clicking System and Maintenance, and then clicking System. Under System, you can view the system type.\r\n<h4>Linux</h4>\r\nDo I really need to tell you? You guys are tech savy enough to Google it and figure it out.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTo test to see if Python installed correctly, go to your Applications and look for "IDLE". If it''s there, congrats, you installed Python!\r\n\r\nIn the next tutorial I''ll be showing you how to create your first program, plus a bit about variables.', 'Learning Python - Part 1 The Installation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '155-revision-15', '', '', '2012-06-15 06:23:53', '2012-06-15 11:23:53', '', 155, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/187/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(181, 14, '2012-06-15 05:42:24', '2012-06-15 10:42:24', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\r\nNote: When I say "shell", "Python shell",  or "interpreter", I mean the window that pops up when you first open IDLE, that takes python lines, and executes them.\r\n\r\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, what is a variable? Well it''s kind of like a container, but more like "tentacle" grasping a value, or no value at at all. Let me give an example, I would suggest entering this into your Python shell to start seeing how the language works. Also just try out a couple things to see if they work, messing around is a great way to explore a language.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\r\nWhen that line is executed by your interpreter, the variable x is "grasping" the string "Hello, world!". A string is a series of characters, grouped together into a single value. In Python, strings are represented by characters between a set of  single ('') or double (") quotes. This means that\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = ''Hello, world!''</pre>\r\nassigns x to the exact same value. One way to find out the value of a variable is to simply enter it into the shell, for example\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\noutputs\r\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\r\nOkay, simple, right? A string isn''t the only type of value that a variable can "grasp". Another  is an integer. Integers are just like they sound, numbers that are round (ie. 1, 2, 3) and can be positive or negative.\r\n<pre></pre>', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-8', '', '', '2012-06-15 05:42:24', '2012-06-15 10:42:24', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/181/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(182, 14, '2012-06-15 05:55:27', '2012-06-15 10:55:27', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\nNote: When I say "shell", "Python shell",  or "interpreter", I mean the window that pops up when you first open IDLE, that takes python lines, and executes them.\n\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, what is a variable? Well it''s kind of like a container, but more like "tentacle" grasping a value, or no value at at all. Let me give an example, I would suggest entering this into your Python shell to start seeing how the language works. Also just try out a couple things to see if they work, messing around is a great way to explore a language.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\nWhen that line is executed by your interpreter, the variable x is "grasping" the string "Hello, world!". A string is a series of characters, grouped together into a single value. In Python, strings are represented by characters between a set of  single ('') or double (") quotes. This means that\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = ''Hello, world!''</pre>\nassigns x to the exact same value. One way to find out the value of a variable is to simply enter it into the shell, for example\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\noutputs\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\nOkay, simple, right? x is just replaced with the value it represents. One interesting thing to do with strings is concatenation. Try typing in the following\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; "Hello," + " world!"</pre>\n<pre>''Hello, world!</pre>\nAdding a plus sign between two strings combines them. Doing the following also work.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello," + "world!"</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\n<pre>''Hello world!''</pre>\nNow lets mess with another type of variable, integers. Integers are just like they sound, numbers that are round (ie. 1, 2, 3) and can be positive or negative.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1</pre>\n<pre>1</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 + 5</pre>\n<pre>6</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 7 * 8</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\n<pre>56</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5 ** 2</pre>\n<pre>25</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 10/2</pre>\n<pre>5</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 6 % 4</pre>\n<pre>2</pre>\nOkay, so for the most part it all works like a calculator. One thing to notice is, in cases like these, whitespace between characters doesn''t really matter. Usually it''s best to put spaces between the different parts just so you can read it, but 1+1 is the same as 1 + 1. All of these characters are called operators by the way, just like in math. The only one you might not have gotten is the % operator, or the modulo operator. All the % does is get the remainder of the division of two numbers (6 / 4 = 1 2/4, so 2 is the remainder).\n<pre></pre>', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-9', '', '', '2012-06-15 05:55:27', '2012-06-15 10:55:27', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/182/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(183, 14, '2012-06-15 05:55:36', '2012-06-15 10:55:36', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\r\nNote: When I say "shell", "Python shell",  or "interpreter", I mean the window that pops up when you first open IDLE, that takes python lines, and executes them.\r\n\r\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, what is a variable? Well it''s kind of like a container, but more like "tentacle" grasping a value, or no value at at all. Let me give an example, I would suggest entering this into your Python shell to start seeing how the language works. Also just try out a couple things to see if they work, messing around is a great way to explore a language.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\r\nWhen that line is executed by your interpreter, the variable x is "grasping" the string "Hello, world!". A string is a series of characters, grouped together into a single value. In Python, strings are represented by characters between a set of  single ('') or double (") quotes. This means that\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = ''Hello, world!''</pre>\r\nassigns x to the exact same value. One way to find out the value of a variable is to simply enter it into the shell, for example\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\noutputs\r\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\r\nOkay, simple, right? x is just replaced with the value it represents. One interesting thing to do with strings is concatenation. Try typing in the following\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; "Hello," + " world!"</pre>\r\n<pre>''Hello, world!</pre>\r\nAdding a plus sign between two strings combines them. Doing the following also work.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello," + "world!"</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\n<pre>''Hello world!''</pre>\r\nNow lets mess with another type of variable, integers. Integers are just like they sound, numbers that are round (ie. 1, 2, 3) and can be positive or negative.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1</pre>\r\n<pre>1</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 + 5</pre>\r\n<pre>6</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 7 * 8</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\n<pre>56</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5 ** 2</pre>\r\n<pre>25</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 10/2</pre>\r\n<pre>5</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 6 % 4</pre>\r\n<pre>2</pre>\r\nOkay, so for the most part it all works like a calculator. One thing to notice is, in cases like these, whitespace between characters doesn''t really matter. Usually it''s best to put spaces between the different parts just so you can read it, but 1+1 is the same as 1 + 1. All of these characters are called operators by the way, just like in math. The only one you might not have gotten is the % operator, or the modulo operator. All the % does is get the remainder of the division of two numbers (6 / 4 = 1 2/4, so 2 is the remainder).\r\n<pre></pre>', 'Learning Python - Part 2 "Hello, world!" and Variables', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-10', '', '', '2012-06-15 05:55:36', '2012-06-15 10:55:36', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/183/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(185, 14, '2012-06-15 06:19:58', '2012-06-15 11:19:58', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\nNote: When I say "shell", "Python shell",  or "interpreter", I mean the window that pops up when you first open IDLE, that takes python lines, and executes them.\n\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, what is a variable? Well it''s kind of like a container, but more like "tentacle" grasping a value, or no value at at all. Let me give an example, I would suggest entering this into your Python shell to start seeing how the language works. Also just try out a couple things to see if they work, messing around is a great way to explore a language.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\nCongratulations, you wrote your first program, albeit a short and not very useful one! When that line is executed by your interpreter, the variable x is "grasping" the string "Hello, world!". A string is a series of characters, grouped together into a single value. In Python, strings are represented by characters between a set of  single ('') or double (") quotes. This means that\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = ''Hello, world!''</pre>\nassigns x to the exact same value. One way to find out the value of a variable is to simply enter it into the shell, for example\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\noutputs\n<pre>''Hello, world!''</pre>\nYou''ll still get ''Hello, world!'' even if you use the double quoted string, they''re identical once you assign them to a variable. Okay, simple, right? x is just replaced with the value it represents. One interesting thing to do with strings is concatenation. Try typing in the following\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; "Hello," + " world!"</pre>\n<pre>''Hello, world!</pre>\nAdding a plus sign between two strings combines them. Doing the following also work.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello," + "world!"</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\n<pre>''Hello world!''</pre>\nNow lets mess with another type of variable, integers. Integers are just like they sound, numbers that are round (ie. 1, 2, 3) and can be positive or negative.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1</pre>\n<pre>1</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 + 5</pre>\n<pre>6</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 7 * 8</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\n<pre>56</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5 ** 2</pre>\n<pre>25</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 10/2</pre>\n<pre>5</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt; 6 % 4</pre>\n<pre>2</pre>\nOkay, so for the most part it all works like a calculator. One thing to notice is, in cases like these, whitespace between characters doesn''t really matter. Usually it''s best to put spaces between the different parts just so you can read it, but 1+1 is the same as 1 + 1. All of these characters are called operators by the way, just like in math. The only one you might not have gotten is the % operator, or the modulo operator. All the % does is get the remainder of the division of two numbers (6 / 4 = 1 2/4, so 2 is the remainder). Let''s try out another variable.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [0, 54, ''foo'', ''bar'']</pre>\nYou just assigned x to what is called a list or an array. A list is a series of different values collected together into a list. You can acces these values like this\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[0]</pre>\n<pre>0</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1]</pre>\n<pre>54</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x [2]</pre>\n<pre>''foo''</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[3]</pre>\n<pre>''bar''</pre>\nEssentially, if a variable is a list and you put brackets after a variable enclosing a number, it will evaluate to the value that''s in that place of your list, minus one! That may seem kind of odd at first, lists counting up from zero. You''ll have to get used to it though, it''s how most programming languages work. It is done that way for a couple of reasons, that will become self apparent once you start working with them more. Lists are also why I say variables are more like "tentacles" that grab values, rather than boxes that hold them.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Learning Python - Part 2 Variables and "Hello, world"', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-11', '', '', '2012-06-15 06:19:58', '2012-06-15 11:19:58', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/185/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
