(186, 14, '2012-06-15 03:03:02', '2012-06-15 08:03:02', '<h2><strong>Why you should want to learn Python</strong></h2>\r\n<em>If you don''t need to be convinced, and just want to start learning the language, I''d suggest just skipping to the next section. If you already know a programing langage, especially if it''s an object oriented one, you can probably just skip or skim the first three or four lessons.</em>\r\n\r\nIf your here as a beginner, maybe I should just explain why you would want to learn how to program. Computers are a huge part of our daily lives, and are pretty important to the workings of the modern world. It would make sense to know how about the inner workings of one, right? What programming allows you to do with computers is incredibly useful and it allows you to use a computers raw power to do exactly what you want. Instead of having to search around for software that does what you want (or even worse do it by hand), you can just write some code that does the job for you. By learning a language, many opportunities open up for you, you can eventually work on making games, or even turn the skill into a profession. Python itself is a great starting language; it has a simple syntax and a gentle learning curve, yet can also be very powerful. After these couple of tutorials, you should be able to start making scripts that are actually useful for you in the real world. Anyway, lets get started!\r\n<h2>Installing Python</h2>\r\nMost computers do not have Python installed when you first get them (only Macs that I know of, and that''s Python 2 .7, which is not what we''ll be using for this), so you''ll have to install it. There are many ways to do this, so I''ll go through a couple. All of it should be fairly simple once you download the file, since it contains a helpful readme.\r\n\r\nFirst, go to Python''s <a title="Python download" href="http://www.python.org/download/">download page</a> and click on the 3.x version for you operating system (currently 3.2.3). Once downloaded, just doubled click the package, and follow the instructions. For Mac and Windows machines, this will be a simple installer like most programs. For Linux, it''s a compressed file that you should unzip and then just follow the readme (but if your running Linux in the first place, you''ll know what to do).\r\n\r\nNote: If you are unsure about whether your computer is 32 or 64 bit, follow these instructions (even though it''s probably 64 bit unless it''s fairly old). Additionally, if you have a package manager installed like homebrew or macports, you can most likely just use that to install Python, just make sure your downloading "python3". You also won''t get the GUI if you use these, but that''s honestly not that bad, the terminal version works just as well, if not better.\r\n<h4>Mac</h4>\r\nGo The Apple <strong>Icon-&gt;About This Mac </strong>and look at your version. If it''s 10.6 or above, go with the 64 bit, otherwise the 32 bit.\r\n<h4>Windows</h4>\r\nOpen System by clicking the Start button <img title="Picture of the Start button" src="http://res2.windows.microsoft.com/resbox/en/Windows%20Vista/main/4f6cbd09-148c-4dd8-b1f2-48f232a2fd33_47.png" alt="Picture of the Start button" width="15" height="15" data-id="pageContainer0_ID0EUE" />, clicking Control Panel, clicking System and Maintenance, and then clicking System. Under System, you can view the system type.\r\n<h4>Linux</h4>\r\nDo I really need to tell you? You guys are tech savy enough to Google it and figure it out.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTo test to see if Python installed correctly, go to your Applications and look for "IDLE". If it''s there, congrats, you installed Python!\r\n\r\nIn the next tutorial I''ll be showing you how to create your first program, plus a bit about variables.', 'Learning Python - Part 1 The Installation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '155-revision-14', '', '', '2012-06-15 03:03:02', '2012-06-15 08:03:02', '', 155, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/186/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
