value is in a list. One thing to keep in mind about list though is that they start counting up from zero. This may seem weird at first, but you''ll get used to it, especially when it becomes useful with looping. I also threw in a little thing that shows that you can assign a specific indice to a value by using bracts after the variable, and then an equal sign with a value after it. One thing that I hope you have noticed is that with all of these things, Python is very insensitive about whitespace, it doesn''t care is there is a space between print and the ("Hello, world!"),or if there is a space between integers and a plus sign, etc. It is usually considered good practice though to put whitespace between operators and values, since it make the code more readable. It is also the norm to not have space between things like print and parenthesis and lists and brackets. One last thing I want to mention is how variables are a little more complex than simply "holding" a value like a container. It is much more accurate to say that are tentacles that "grab" a value in the memory of your computer. I think the following example will make this idea a little more clear.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [1, 2, 3]</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;y = x</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1] = 0</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y</pre>\n<pre>[1, 0, 3]</pre>\nAs you can see, y and x "held" the same value in memory, when you change one, you change the other. If you want to copy a list, it is best to do the following:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [0, 1, 2]</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y = list(x)</pre>\nAnyway, my next tutorial will be on what things like "list" and "print" are (spoiler: they\n\n&nbsp;', 'Learning Python - Part 2 Variables and "Hello, world"', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-14', '', '', '2012-06-15 07:33:02', '2012-06-15 12:33:02', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/191/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
