is just replaces x with what it is holding. The reason that it appears in single quotes ('') instead of double quotes (") is because, in Python, the two are synonymous. When a string is called from memory it is displayed with single quotes because Python doesn''t care what type of quotes were used to create it. However, simply typing in a variable to display it''s contents is not a good idea. If you were to save this as a file and run it then nothing would show up. Only if you were to change it to:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(x)</pre>\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\nwould it actually print something to the screen. One thing you might have noticed is that print() still works even if it''s not a string that is being placed inside the parenthesis. This is because x is evaluated to it''s value during the process of executing the line, turning it into\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(''Hello, world!'')</pre>\nsame as before. One thing I''ll mention about strings is that they have a couple of operators that do things to them.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;"foo " + "bar"</pre>\n<pre>''foo bar''</pre>\nAs you can see, adding a plus sign between two strings adds them together, or concatenates them. You can also multiply a string by a number.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; ''foo'' * 7</pre>\n<pre>foofoofoofoofoofoofoo</pre>\nThis just causes the string to repeat itself the number of times it was multiplied by. This "operator" (the *, or multiply) can take one string and one or more of what is called an integer. The + operator can take two or more strings. These integers are not only for multiplying strings, they are also used for most addition and subtraction in Python.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 + 2</pre>\n<pre>3</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x=1</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x + 2</pre>\n<pre>3</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 - 1</pre>\n<pre>0</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 * 5</pre>\n<pre>5</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5 ** 2</pre>\n<pre>25</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 6 % 4</pre>\n<pre>2</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 10 / 2</pre>\n<pre>5.0</pre>\nThose examples are fairly self evident (except maybe the last three). The ** operator is for exponentiation (5^2), the % is the modulo operator which gets the remainder of the devision of two numbers (6 / 4 = 1 2/4 = remainder 2), and the / is division. Why does its output have a .0 after it though? This is because in Python, when a number is divided, the result is automatically converted to a "float", or a floating point number. These are numbers that have decimal points after them. You can use the same operators for floats as you do for integers\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 - 4</pre>\n<pre>1.2</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 5.1</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x - 1.1</pre>\n<pre>4.0</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 + 1.0</pre>\n<pre>6.2</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 / 4</pre>\n<pre>1.3</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 * 3.2</pre>\n<pre>16.64</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 ** 2</pre>\n<pre>27.040000000000003</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 % 4</pre>\n<pre>1.2000000000000002</pre>\nOne thing to note is that if you have an operation between an integer and a float the integer is automatically turned into a float. Other things that are very problematic are the last two examples. The value outputted is obviously wrong! This is due to the way the Python rounds numbers and, unfortunately, this is unavoidable. This is why it is usually best to calculate things with integers if you can. One more type of variable is the list (or array).\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [3, 5, 3, 1, ''a'']</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[0]</pre>\n<pre>3</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1]</pre>\n<pre>5</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[2]</pre>\n<pre>3</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x [3]</pre>\n<pre>1</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[4]</pre>\n<pre>''a''</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1] = 4</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1]</pre>\n<pre>4</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\n<pre>[3, 4, 3, 1, ''a'']</pre>\nSo x is assigned to a list containing 3, 4, 3, 1, and the string "a" in that order. To access an item in the list you put the name of the list and then an indice in brackets after the list. An indice is just the place of a value is in a list. One thing to keep in mind about list though is that they start counting up from zero. This may seem weird at first, but you''ll get used to it, especially when it becomes useful with looping. I also threw in a little thing that shows that you can assign a specific indice to a value by using bracts after the variable, and then an equal sign with a value after it. One thing that I hope you have noticed is that with all of these things, Python is very insensitive about white space. It doesn''t care if there is a space between print and the ("Hello, world!"),or if there is a space between integers and a plus sign, etc. It is usually considered good practice though to put white space between operators and values, since it make the code more readable. It is also the norm to not have space between things like print and parenthesis and lists and brackets. One last thing I want to mention is how variables are a little more complex than simply "holding" a value like a container. It is much more accurate to say that are tentacles that "grab" a value in the memory of your computer. I think the following example will make this idea a little more clear.\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [1, 2, 3]</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;y = x</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1] = 0</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y</pre>\n<pre>[1, 0, 3]</pre>\nAs you can see, y and x "held" the same value in memory, when you change one, you change the other. If you want to copy a list, it is best to do the following:\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [0, 1, 2]</pre>\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y = list(x)</pre>\nJust a link for the more adventurous; I highly suggest you take a look at the Python <a title="Python 3 Documentation" href="http://docs.python.org/py3k/">documentation</a> if you are ever feeling curious, it''s great stuff!\n\nAnyway, my next tutorial will be on what things like "list" and "print" are (spoiler: they''re functions!).\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Learning Python 