(202, 4, '2012-06-15 09:37:12', '2012-06-15 14:37:12', '<h2><strong>Why you should want to learn Python (or any programming language)</strong></h2>\r\n<em>If you don''t need to be convinced, and just want to start learning the language, I''d suggest just skipping to the next section. If you already know a programing langage, especially if it''s an object oriented one, you can probably just skip or skim the first three or four lessons.</em>\r\n\r\nComputers are a huge part of our daily lives, and are pretty important in the workings of the modern world. It would make sense to know about the inner workings of one, right? What programming allows you to do with computers is incredibly useful lets you to use a computers raw power more efficiently. Instead of having to search around for software that does what you want (or even worse do it by hand), you can just write some code that does the job for you. By learning a language, many opportunities open up for you, you can eventually work on making games, or even turn the skill into a profession. Python itself is a great starting language; it has a simple syntax and a gentle learning curve, yet can also be very powerful. After these couple of tutorials, you should be able to start making scripts that are actually useful for you in the real world. Anyway, lets get started!\r\n<h2>Installing Python</h2>\r\nMost computers do not have Python installed when you first get them (only Macs that I know of, and that''s Python 2 .7, which is not what we''ll be using for this), so you''ll have to install it. There are many ways to do this, so I''ll go through a couple. All of it should be fairly simple once you download the file, since it contains a helpful readme.\r\n\r\nFirst, go to Python''s <a title="Python download" href="http://www.python.org/download/">download page</a> and click on the 3.x version for you operating system (currently 3.2.3). Once downloaded, just doubled click the package, and follow the instructions. For Mac and Windows machines, this will be a simple installer like most programs. For Linux, it''s a compressed file that you should unzip and then just follow the readme (but if your running Linux in the first place, you''ll know what to do).\r\n\r\nNote: If you are unsure about whether your computer is 32 or 64 bit, follow these instructions (even though it''s probably 64 bit unless it''s fairly old). Additionally, if you have a package manager installed like homebrew or macports, you can most likely just use that to install Python, just make sure your downloading "python3" not "python". You also won''t get the GUI if you use these, but that''s honestly not that bad, the terminal version works just as well, if not better.\r\n<h4>Mac</h4>\r\nGo The Apple <strong>Icon-&gt;About This Mac </strong>and look at your version. If it''s 10.6 or above, go with the 64 bit, otherwise the 32 bit.\r\n<h4>Windows</h4>\r\nOpen System by clicking the Start button <img title="Picture of the Start button" src="http://res2.windows.microsoft.com/resbox/en/Windows%20Vista/main/4f6cbd09-148c-4dd8-b1f2-48f232a2fd33_47.png" alt="Picture of the Start button" width="15" height="15" data-id="pageContainer0_ID0EUE" />, clicking Control Panel, clicking System and Maintenance, and then clicking System. Under System, you can view the system type.\r\n<h4>Linux</h4>\r\nJust use uname and see if x86_64 is in the output, if it is, your probably running a 64 bit kernel).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTo test to see if Python installed correctly, go to your Applications and look for "IDLE" (unless you installed it with a packet manager, then just go into your terminal and try typing in "python3" or "python". If it''s there, congrats, you installed Python!\r\n\r\nIn the next tutorial I''ll be showing you how to create your (very simple) first program, plus a bit about variables.', 'Learning Python - Part 1 The Installation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '155-revision-18', '', '', '2012-06-15 09:37:12', '2012-06-15 14:37:12', '', 155, 'http://www.slushie.me/2012/202/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(203, 4, '2012-06-15 11:21:15', '2012-06-15 16:21:15', '<h2><strong>Why you should want to learn Python (or any programming language)</strong></h2>\r\n<em>If you don''t need to be convinced, and just want to start learning the language, I''d suggest just skipping to the next section. If you already know a programming language, especially if it''s an object oriented one, you can probably just skip or skim the first three or four lessons.</em>\r\n\r\nComputers are a huge part of our daily lives, and are pretty important in the workings of the modern world. It would make sense to know about the inner workings of one, right? What programming allows you to do with computers is incredibly useful. It lets you use a computer''s raw power more efficiently. Instead of having to search around for software that does what you want you can just write some code that does the job for you. By learning a language, opportunities open up for you. You can eventually work on making games. This is the type of skill that turns into a profession. Python itself is a great starting language; it has a simple syntax and a gentle learning curve. This is not to say it can''t also be very powerful. After these couple of tutorials, you should be able to start making scripts that are actually useful for you in the real world. \\\r\n\r\nAnyway, lets get started!\r\n<h2>Installing Python</h2>\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Python.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-198" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Python.png" alt="" width="292" height="223" /></a>\r\n\r\nMost computers do not have Python installed when you first get them (only Macs that I know of, and that''s Python 2 .7, which is not what we''ll be using for this). You''ll have to install it. There are many ways to do this, so I''ll go through a couple. All of it should be fairly simple once you download the file, since it contains a helpful readme.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li> Go to Python''s <a title="Python download" href="http://www.python.org/download/">download page</a> and click on the 3.x version for you operating system (currently 3.2.3).</li>\r\n	<li>Once downloaded, just doubled click the package, and follow the instructions.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Pythonpage.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-200" title="Pythonpage" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Pythonpage-300x93.png" alt="" width="300" height="93" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor Mac and Windows machines, this will be a simple installer like most programs. For Linux, it''s a compressed file that you should unzip and then just follow the readme (but if your running Linux in the first place, you''ll know what to do).\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Downloads.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-201" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Downloads-300x180.png" alt="" width="300" height="180" /></a>\r\n\r\nNote: If you are unsure about whether your computer is 32 or 64 bit, follow these instructions (even though it''s probably 64 bit unless it''s fairly old). Additionally, if you have a package manager installed like homebrew or macports, you can most likely just use that to install Python, just make sure your downloading "python3" not "python". You also won''t get the GUI if you use these, but that''s honestly not that bad, the terminal version works just as well, if not better.\r\n<h4>Mac</h4>\r\nGo The Apple <strong>Icon-&gt;About This Mac </strong>and look at your version. If it''s 10.6 or above, go with the 64 bit, otherwise the 32 bit.\r\n<h4>Windows</h4>\r\nOpen System by clicking the Start button <img title="Picture of the Start button" src="http://res2.windows.microsoft.com/resbox/en/Windows%20Vista/main/4f6cbd09-148c-4dd8-b1f2-48f232a2fd33_47.png" alt="Picture of the Start button" width="15" height="15" data-id="pageContainer0_ID0EUE" />. Click Control Panel. Click System and Security, and then click System. Under System, you can view the system type.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/System-and-Security.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-199" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/System-and-Security-300x113.png" alt="" width="300" height="113" /></a>\r\n<h4>Linux</h4>\r\nJust use uname and see if x86_64 is in the output, if it is, your probably running a 64 bit kernel).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTo test to see if Python installed correctly, go to your Applications and look for "IDLE" (unless you installed it with a packet manager, then just go into your terminal and try typing in "python3" or "python". If it''s there, congrats, you installed Python!\r\n\r\nIn the next tutorial I''ll be showing you how to create your (very simple) first program, plus a bit about variables.', 'Learning Python - Part 1 The Installation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '155-revision-19', '', '', '2012-06-15 11:21:15', '2012-06-15 16:21:15', '', 155, 'http://www.slushie.me/203/155-revision-19/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(204, 2, '2012-06-15 09:53:24', '2012-06-15 14:53:24', '<h1>To those who it may concern, this article is not yet finished. I plan on completing it either sometime during my vacation abroad, or as soon as I get back.</h1>\r\nSo in the last tutorial I spoke briefly about functions. Functions are simply blocks of code that can be run with different values. For example, say I have a function called square. It is passed two numbers, the base and power of an exponent. It then returns the result in Python, it would look like the following:\r\n<pre>def square(base, power):</pre>\r\n<pre>    return (base ** power)</pre>\r\n<pre># An example of its usage</pre>\r\n<pre>print(square(2, 4))</pre>\r\n<pre>#Outputs 16</pre>\r\nIf you plan on running this, I suggest creating a .py file and using that. In the IDLE, just press command/control-N, although you can also use a <strong>plain text</strong> editor, you must make sure you are not using rich text, or else the file will not be executable. Make sure to save the file as whateverYouWant.py so it will open in IDLE or a shell.\r\n\r\nNow, I''ll walk through what is going on.', 'Learning Python - Part 3 Functions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '196-revision-2', '', '', '2012-06-15 09:53:24', '2012-06-15 14:53:24', '', 196, 'http://www.slushie.me/204/196-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(205, 2, '2012-06-15 09:40:03', '2012-06-15 14:40:03', '<h2>Your first program</h2>\r\nBefore we write a customary "Hello, world!" program, I want to go over a couple of things about variables. First of all, start up IDLE or terminal. A window should appear with something like this at the top:\r\n<pre>Python 3.2.3 (v3.2.3:3d0686d90f55, Apr 10 2012, 11:25:50) \r\n[GCC 4.2.1 (Your Operating System build 5666) (dot 3)] on your kernel\r\nType "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.</pre>\r\nAfter that, you should see three carrots (&gt;&gt;&gt;). That is the prompt for you to enter a command into the window, or what is called the shell. It actually has a couple other names, like "interpreter" or "terminal", that I will use interchangeably when referring to it. When there is text you should enter into the shell it will appear like\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; this</pre>\r\nAny outputs in response from the shell will look like\r\n<pre>this</pre>\r\nSounds good, lets get started. First lets create the traditional "Hello, world!" program that prints "Hello, world!". In some languages like C, this program could take up several lines. In Python though, it only takes up one.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print ("Hello, world!")</pre>\r\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\r\nFor this tutorial, I''m mainly going to talk about the "Hello, world!" part of all that, I''ll explain more about print() in the next tutorial. "Hello, world!" is what you would call a string, a string of characters. These strings can be assigned to a variable. What is a variable? A variable is container that hold a value (it''s actually a bit more complex than that, I''ll explain at the end of this tutorial). So when you execute the following in the shell\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = "Hello, world!"</pre>\r\nYou are stroring the string "Hello, world!" in variable x. To call that string again from that variable, just type\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\n<pre>''Hello, world''</pre>\r\nThis just replaces x with what it is holding. The reason that it appears in single quotes ('') instead of double quotes (") is because in Python, the two are synonymous. When a string is called from memory, it is displayed with single quotes, because Python doesn''t care what type of quotes were used to create it. One thing to not is that simply typing in a variable to display it''s contents is not a good idea, if you were to save this as a file and run it, nothing would show up. Only if you were to change it to\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(x)</pre>\r\n<pre>Hello, world!</pre>\r\nwould it actually print something to the screen. One thing you might have noticed is that print() still works even if it''s not a string that is being placed inside the parenthesis. This is because x is evaluated to it''s value during the process of executing the line, turning it into\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; print(''Hello, world!'')</pre>\r\nsame as before. One thing I''ll mention about strings is that they have a couple of operators that do things to them.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;"foo " + "bar"</pre>\r\n<pre>''foo bar''</pre>\r\nAs you can see, adding a plus sign between two strings adds them together, or concatenates them. You can also multiply a string by a number.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; ''foo'' * 7</pre>\r\n<pre>foofoofoofoofoofoofoo</pre>\r\nThis just causes the string to repeat itself the number of times it was multiplied by. This "operator" (the *, or multiply) can take one string and one or more of what is called an integer. The + operator can take two or more strings. These integers are not only for multiplying strings, they are also used for most addition and subtraction in Python.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 + 2</pre>\r\n<pre>3</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x=1</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x + 2</pre>\r\n<pre>3</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 - 1</pre>\r\n<pre>0</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 1 * 5</pre>\r\n<pre>5</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5 ** 2</pre>\r\n<pre>25</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 6 % 4</pre>\r\n<pre>2</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 10 / 2</pre>\r\n<pre>5.0</pre>\r\nThose examples are fairly self evident, except maybe the last three. The ** operator is for exponentiation (5^2), the % is the modulo operator which gets the remainder of the devision of two numbers (6 / 4 = 1 2/4, so the remainder is 2), and the / is devision. Why does it''s output have a .0 after it though? This is because in Python, when a number is divided, the result is automatically converted to a "float", or a floating point number. These are numbers that have decimal points after them. You can use the same operators for floats as you do for integers\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 - 4</pre>\r\n<pre>1.2</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 5.1</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x - 1.1</pre>\r\n<pre>4.0</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 + 1.0</pre>\r\n<pre>6.2</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 / 4</pre>\r\n<pre>1.3</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 * 3.2</pre>\r\n<pre>16.64</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 ** 2</pre>\r\n<pre>27.040000000000003</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; 5.2 % 4</pre>\r\n<pre>1.2000000000000002</pre>\r\nOne thing to note is that if you have an operation between an integer and a float, the integer is automatically turned into a float. Another thing that is very problematic is that last two examples. The value outputted is obviously wrong! This is due to the way the Python rounds numbers, and is unavoidable. This is why it is usually best to calculate things with integers, if you can. One more type of variable; the list, or array.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [3, 5, 3, 1, ''a'']</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[0]</pre>\r\n<pre>3</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1]</pre>\r\n<pre>5</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[2]</pre>\r\n<pre>3</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x [3]</pre>\r\n<pre>1</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[4]</pre>\r\n<pre>''a''</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1] = 4</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1]</pre>\r\n<pre>4</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x</pre>\r\n<pre>[3, 4, 3, 1, ''a'']</pre>\r\nSo x is assigned to a list containing 3, 4, 3, 1, and the string "a" in that order. To acces an item in the list, you put the name of the list, and then an indice in brackets after the list. An indice is just the place of a value is in a list. One thing to keep in mind about list though is that they start counting up from zero. This may seem weird at first, but you''ll get used to it, especially when it becomes useful with looping. I also threw in a little thing that shows that you can assign a specific indice to a value by using bracts after the variable, and then an equal sign with a value after it. One thing that I hope you have noticed is that with all of these things, Python is very insensitive about whitespace, it doesn''t care is there is a space between print and the ("Hello, world!"),or if there is a space between integers and a plus sign, etc. It is usually considered good practice though to put whitespace between operators and values, since it make the code more readable. It is also the norm to not have space between things like print and parenthesis and lists and brackets. One last thing I want to mention is how variables are a little more complex than simply "holding" a value like a container. It is much more accurate to say that are tentacles that "grab" a value in the memory of your computer. I think the following example will make this idea a little more clear.\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [1, 2, 3]</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt;y = x</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x[1] = 0</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y</pre>\r\n<pre>[1, 0, 3]</pre>\r\nAs you can see, y and x "held" the same value in memory, when you change one, you change the other. If you want to copy a list, it is best to do the following:\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; x = [0, 1, 2]</pre>\r\n<pre>&gt;&gt;&gt; y = list(x)</pre>\r\nJust a link for the more adventurous; I highly suggest you take a look at the Python <a title="Python 3 Documentation" href="http://docs.python.org/py3k/">documentation</a> if you are ever feeling curious, it''s great stuff!\r\n\r\nAnyway, my next tutorial will be on what things like "list" and "print" are (spoiler: they''re functions!).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Learning Python - Part 2 Variables and "Hello, world"', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '171-revision-17', '', '', '2012-06-15 09:40:03', '2012-06-15 14:40:03', '', 171, 'http://www.slushie.me/205/171-revision-17/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(206, 4, '2012-06-15 11:25:30', '2012-06-15 16:25:30', '<h2><strong>Why you should want to learn Python (or any programming language)</strong></h2>\r\n<em>If you don''t need to be convinced, and just want to start learning the language, I''d suggest just skipping to the next section. If you already know a programming language, especially if it''s an object oriented one, you can probably just skip or skim the first three or four lessons.</em>\r\n\r\nComputers are a huge part of our daily lives, and are pretty important in the workings of the modern world. It would make sense to know about the inner workings of one, right? What programming allows you to do with computers is incredibly useful. It lets you use a computer''s raw power more efficiently. Instead of having to search around for software that does what you want you can just write some code that does the job for you. By learning a language, opportunities open up for you. You can eventually work on making games. This is the type of skill that turns into a profession. Python itself is a great starting language; it has a simple syntax and a gentle learning curve. This is not to say it can''t also be very powerful. After these couple of tutorials, you should be able to start making scripts that are actually useful for you in the real world. \\\r\n\r\nAnyway, lets get started!\r\n<h2>Installing Python</h2>\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Python.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-198" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Python.png" alt="" width="292" height="223" /></a>\r\n\r\nMost computers do not have Python installed when you first get them (only Macs that I know of, and that''s Python 2 .7, which is not what we''ll be using for this). You''ll have to install it. There are many ways to do this, so I''ll go through a couple. All of it should be fairly simple once you download the file, since it contains a helpful readme.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li> Go to Python''s <a title="Python download" href="http://www.python.org/download/">download page</a> and click on the 3.x version for you operating system (currently 3.2.3).</li>\r\n	<li>Once downloaded, just doubled click the package, and follow the instructions.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Pythonpage.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-200" title="Pythonpage" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Pythonpage-300x93.png" alt="" width="300" height="93" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor Mac and Windows machines, this will be a simple installer like most programs. For Linux, it''s a compressed file that you should unzip and then just follow the readme (but if your running Linux in the first place, you''ll know what to do).\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Downloads.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-201" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Downloads-300x180.png" alt="" width="300" height="180" /></a>\r\n\r\nNote: If you are unsure about whether your computer is 32 or 64 bit, follow these instructions (even though it''s probably 64 bit unless it''s fairly old). Additionally, if you have a package manager installed like homebrew or macports, you can most likely just use that to install Python, just make sure your downloading "python3" not "python". You also won''t get the GUI if you use these, but that''s honestly not that bad, the terminal version works just as well, if not better.\r\n<h4>Mac</h4>\r\nGo The Apple <strong>Icon-&gt;About This Mac </strong>and look at your version. If it''s 10.6 or above, go with the 64 bit, otherwise the 32 bit.\r\n<h4>Windows</h4>\r\nOpen System by clicking the Start button <img title="Picture of the Start button" src="http://res2.windows.microsoft.com/resbox/en/Windows%20Vista/main/4f6cbd09-148c-4dd8-b1f2-48f232a2fd33_47.png" alt="Picture of the Start button" width="15" height="15" data-id="pageContainer0_ID0EUE" />. Click Control Panel. Click System and Security, and then click System. Under System, you can view the system type.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/System-and-Security.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-199" title="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/System-and-Security-300x113.png" alt="" width="300" height="113" /></a>\r\n<h4>Linux</h4>\r\nJust use uname and see if x86_64 is in the output, if it is, your probably running a 64 bit kernel).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTo test to see if Python installed correctly, go to your Applications and look for "IDLE" (unless you installed it with a packet manager, then just go into your terminal and try typing in "python3" or "python". If it''s there, congrats, you installed Python!\r\n\r\nIn the next tutorial I''ll be showing you how to create your (very simple) first program, plus a bit about variables.', 'Learning Python - Part 1 The Installation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '155-revision-20', '', '', '2012-06-15 11:25:30', '2012-06-15 16:25:30', '', 155, 'http://www.slushie.me/206/155-revision-20/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
