(235, 2, '2012-06-27 22:42:13', '2012-06-28 03:42:13', '<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25-Orion.png"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-234" title="Orion: Music + More" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25-Orion-1024x455.png" alt="" width="1024" height="455" /></a>This past Saturday I was lucky enough to go to the Orion Music + More festival hosted in Atlantic City, NJ by Metallica. While I only got to go for the first day/night, I do feel that I saw almost everything I would want to see in the festival, with the exception of Volbeat. What I am wondering, is if this will become some awesome annual event.\n\n<strong>The Setup</strong>\n\nThe festival was hosted in Bader Field, about a mile or two from the main strip of Atlantic City. The setup was surprisingly good. In many festivals, one must walk <em>around</em> a lot of large tents or VIP areas or other obstructions that make crossing the area to go to different events rather difficult or annoying. This had none of those issues. The field was setup not much unlike a regular pentagon: the stages made up the top three points, with the main stage at the left most, the Fuel stage to the right of that, and the Damage Inc. stage to the right of that. The bottom left corner was the entrance. The other three sides were made of concessions, swag booths, and lots and lots of porta-potties. (For those aficionados out there, they were of the “Mr. John” variety.) There were a couple of small tents and rows of booths in the middle that made a larger space for the main stage and shrunk the other two a bit, however, as I said, the setup was great.\n\n<strong>The Performers</strong>\n\nPersonally the best of all of the performers was, next to Metallica of course, the Arctic Monkeys. Recently-ish I have started listening to their stuff and have been really liking it. When I heard that they were going to be there with Metallica that sounded awesome. And they were. The lead singer was extremely charismatic and had a great stage presence after Lars introduced him and the band with some self-deprecating humor. However, they were only the last band to play before Metallica. While there I also got a chance to see some artists I had and hadn’t heard of before. I got the chance to see Gaslight Anthem, of whom I had not previously heard, but I quite liked them. The singer was rather fun to watch and seemed to be having a genuinely good time. I saw Cage the Elephant, of whom I know nothing about beyond their two songs that have gotten some popular radio play. Sadly, though, they were pretty awful. The ADHD of the singer made it simultaneously rather difficult to watch and somewhat boring. However, just as I started getting bored I noticed the deaf interpreter on the side of the stage. We decided to name her Ellen. Ellen was awesome. Now, I had seen some deaf interpreters at some other concerts, such as AC/DC, but none of them could even touch Ellen’s extreme enthusiasm and rock. She was possibly rocking out even harder than the probably wasted band. When there was no singing, she played air guitar. When there was, she signed and headbanged all at the same time. It was a rather amazing spectacle. However, about three songs in poor ellen must have tired herself as she was replaced by her rather boring counterpart, whom we named Barbara. Then we walked on to see Suicidal Tendencies. I didn’t like them. Now, it wasn’t the music so much as the extremely annoying lead. He kept running around stage in a semicircle which, due to his slight rotunditude, made him out of breath so his singing was a bit ragged by the end. However, beyond this, he also had an annoying monologue/talk-with-the-audience-prelude before one of his songs about the meaning of freedom. It was not only stupid, long, and something I totally don’t agree with, but it also seemed that he was trying far to hard to be deep in a way that he clearly wasn’t. Then Trujillo came on stage and did some bass for them for a couple of songs. (I later found out that Trujillo had been a member of Suicidal Tendencies before Metallica and the death of Cliff Burton.) Sadly, I did miss Modest Mouse, but from what I heard across the lawn they sounded good.\n\n<strong>Metallica</strong>\n\nDown right amazing and awesome. I feel almost lucky to be among the first people ever to hear Escape performed live, however that pales in comparison to the overall awesome rock-your-face-off-itude of their whole show. The night I saw was the night they played the entire Ride The Lightning album, thus their necessity for playing Escape. But they also played all of their awesome songs too. They played Enter Sandman which made me nearly weep as that is without a doubt my favorite song. However they also did Sad But True, Master of Puppets and a ton of really great songs. Yet, the encore was the best part of the whole show. For the encore they played One, my second favorite song, with an awesome laser and pyrotechnics show. They ended with Seek and Destroy. The concert was entirely cool and badass except for one part: his thank-you about half-way through. Now, I tend to think of James Hetfield as an awesome metal god and a badass. However, when he improvs apparently his inner dork begins to glow and we all definitely saw it through his leather vest. He started a call and repeat in the middle of one of the songs (I forget which) that began as simply a part of the song. Yet, this quickly devolved into him saying, nay, <em>chanting</em> things at the audience such as “Metallicuuuhhh,” “Metallicuuuhhh and Oriooonnn,” “Togetheratlast,” “Metallicafamily,” “Orion famuhlay,” “One big famuhlay.” (Those are attempted phoneticisms, not actual spellings.) Oh Jesus was it painful. Not only was he shedding some of his awesome in exchange for a dork hat, but in addition the crowd petered out after “Metcallicuuuhhh and Oriooonnn.” Oh well, the concert was so awesome taken as a whole.\n\n<strong>The Wrap</strong>\n\nWhile I didn’t see Barbara or Ellen at any of the other stages, I hear they did make more appearances that night and the next. They complement each other nicely. I think the festival was a total blast and a huge success, but I am not sure if it was planned to be annual. If it was, I think it definitely will and hope to see Barbara there again, but possibly not see Atlantic City. If that is the price I have to pay for Barbara and Metallica, then so be it.', 'Orion: Music + More', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '233-revision', '', '', '2012-06-27 22:42:13', '2012-06-28 03:42:13', '', 233, 'http://www.slushie.me/235/233-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(236, 2, '2012-06-27 22:48:08', '2012-06-28 03:48:08', '<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25Only-On-The-Surface.png"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-237" title="Only On The Surface" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25Only-On-The-Surface-1024x455.png" alt="" width="1024" height="455" /></a>For many reasons, this is going to be a rather short analysis. The first is that I don’t really feel the need to cover Windows 8 as we have been seeing that slip around over the course of almost the past year. That and that there isn’t a lot to cover. I just feel that beyond some small cool things, the Microsoft Surface hasn’t done a lot of things that are <em>huge</em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Thoughts</strong>\r\n\r\nThe keynote was pretty dull. I think they were going for a “we beat Apple” feel, but there are a lot of things that made me feel otherwise. The first of these is that while Balmer was on stage reading statistics, he wasn’t doing just that. He was also giving some weird emotional spiel that seemed poorly rehearsed. The video was decent. The issue is that Apple keynotes spew tremendous graphs and factoids about how much better they are doing than the competition, being keen to leave out any downfalls. Yet, Microsoft seemed to fail at really conveying the message that “we beat them.” Besides, Balmer has no charisma or stage presence. The other things that makes me feel that they failed to “beat Apple” is that every time I caught a glimpse of the audience, all I saw were journalists and reporters, etc. either looking up or down at glowing Apple logos. Oh, and the fact that the unacceptable happened: the product malfunctioned. Midway through the presentation, there was some sort of fumble and the Surface device became inoperable. I think the screen froze. Its a bit sad that that happened.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/ms-surface.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-240" title="Surface" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/ms-surface.jpg" alt="" width="980" height="717" /></a>The Device</strong>\r\n\r\nThe device really is new “only on the Surface” for a bunch of reasons. While I do really like the new Windows logo and the cool dock/magnet connector for the even cooler and more ingenious keyboard/cover attachment, there was nothing that actually worked to make me think they are really pushing the envelope.\r\n\r\nFirst to the good things, though. The keyboard that is supplied with the device is some brilliant combination of Apple’s own SmartCover and Zagg’s ZaggMate (yes there <em>are</em> tons of other devices like Zagg’s). It connects on the long side of the rather rectangular device with a magnetic/pin dock situation and serves to both flap over the screen and cover/protect it and to also flap out as a keyboard and trackpad. Brilliance. The device also has a built in kickstand. This is where I’m really not sure. It is a large enough device that if it broke it would be really annoying, but Redmond was really showing off the strength of the special “VaporMg” casing. HTC did the same with some of their smartphones, so I could see this ending up well or poorly. As always it’s really thin and has a high-def screen and blah blah blah (the screen is actually pretty nice, with an ‘HD’ display at 16:9 and 10.6”, nevertheless). All those things seem pretty normal to me for any contemporary tablet release. However, the addition of a USB port is really awesome. I am not entirely ready to dispense of man’s second best friend (the flashdrive). The SD slot seems a bit out dated. That seems to be the issue with a lot of Microsoft’s products and attitude as a whole. They can’t make anything truly new because they won’t dispense of things we think of needing right now, but probably wont use in five years. But if they do, then people complain because Windows machines are the standard and people don’t expect them to drop things just because they are old. However when Apple does this it’s “only to be expected, it’s Apple.” Rather much of an unfair double-standard they have to deal with. The cameras seem pretty average, just like a lot of the other hardware, if not on the upper-end.\r\n\r\nNow to the (bad) mediocre. There isn’t anything about the device that seems inherently bad or stupid, but a lot of it just seems like the same-ol’ same-ol’. This might change when the device is actually released, but we shall see.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Wrap</strong>\r\n\r\nIn the end, I think this is still a pretty spectacular device, simply because of Windows 8 RT and its low power capacities, though Windows 8 Pro is still awesome. If anyone wants a new tablet that works more as a hardcore computer then this seems like the definite choice, as there is nothing actually <em>bad</em> about the device, and, just like any new device, it will only be “cutting-edge” for so long.', 'Only On The Surface', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'only-on-the-surface', '', '', '2012-06-27 22:50:33', '2012-06-28 03:50:33', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=236', 0, 'post', '', 0),
