(251, 2, '2012-08-29 13:43:37', '2012-08-29 18:43:37', '<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25-Orion.png"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-234" title="Orion: Music + More" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2012-06-25-Orion-1024x455.png" alt="" width="1024" height="455" /></a>This past Saturday I was lucky enough to go to the Orion Music + More festival hosted in Atlantic City, NJ by Metallica. While I only got to go for the first day/night, I do feel that I saw almost everything I would want to see in the festival, with the exception of Volbeat. What I am wondering, is if this will become some awesome annual event. <strong>The Setup</strong> The festival was hosted in Bader Field, about a mile or two from the main strip of Atlantic City. The setup was surprisingly good. In many festivals, one must walk <em>around</em> a lot of large tents or VIP areas or other obstructions that make crossing the area to go to different events rather difficult or annoying. This had none of those issues. The field was setup not much unlike a regular pentagon: the stages made up the top three points, with the main stage at the left most, the Fuel stage to the right of that, and the Damage Inc. stage to the right of that. The bottom left corner was the entrance. The other three sides were made of concessions, swag booths, and lots and lots of porta-potties. (For those aficionados out there, they were of the “Mr. John” variety.) There were a couple of small tents and rows of booths in the middle that made a larger space for the main stage and shrunk the other two a bit, however, as I said, the setup was great. <strong>The Performers</strong> Personally the best of all of the performers was, next to Metallica of course, the Arctic Monkeys. Recently-ish I have started listening to their stuff and have been really liking it. When I heard that they were going to be there with Metallica that sounded awesome. And they were. The lead singer was extremely charismatic and had a great stage presence after Lars introduced him and the band with some self-deprecating humor. However, they were only the last band to play before Metallica. While there I also got a chance to see some artists I had and hadn’t heard of before. I got the chance to see Gaslight Anthem, of whom I had not previously heard, but I quite liked them. The singer was rather fun to watch and seemed to be having a genuinely good time. I saw Cage the Elephant, of whom I know nothing about beyond their two songs that have gotten some popular radio play. Sadly, though, they were pretty awful. The ADHD of the singer made it simultaneously rather difficult to watch and somewhat boring. However, just as I started getting bored I noticed the deaf interpreter on the side of the stage. We decided to name her Ellen. Ellen was awesome. Now, I had seen some deaf interpreters at some other concerts, such as AC/DC, but none of them could even touch Ellen’s extreme enthusiasm and rock. She was possibly rocking out even harder than the probably wasted band. When there was no singing, she played air guitar. When there was, she signed and headbanged all at the same time. It was a rather amazing spectacle. However, about three songs in poor ellen must have tired herself as she was replaced by her rather boring counterpart, whom we named Barbara. Then we walked on to see Suicidal Tendencies. I didn’t like them. Now, it wasn’t the music so much as the extremely annoying lead. He kept running around stage in a semicircle which, due to his slight rotunditude, made him out of breath so his singing was a bit ragged by the end. However, beyond this, he also had an annoying monologue/talk-with-the-audience-prelude before one of his songs about the meaning of freedom. It was not only stupid, long, and something I totally don’t agree with, but it also seemed that he was trying far to hard to be deep in a way that he clearly wasn’t. Then Trujillo came on stage and did some bass for them for a couple of songs. (I later found out that Trujillo had been a member of Suicidal Tendencies before Metallica and the death of Cliff Burton.) Sadly, I did miss Modest Mouse, but from what I heard across the lawn they sounded good. <strong>Metallica</strong> Down right amazing and awesome. I feel almost lucky to be among the first people ever to hear Escape performed live, however that pales in comparison to the overall awesome rock-your-face-off-itude of their whole show. The night I saw was the night they played the entire Ride The Lightning album, thus their necessity for playing Escape. But they also played all of their awesome songs too. They played Enter Sandman which made me nearly weep as that is without a doubt my favorite song. However they also did Sad But True, Master of Puppets and a ton of really great songs. Yet, the encore was the best part of the whole show. For the encore they played One, my second favorite song, with an awesome laser and pyrotechnics show. They ended with Seek and Destroy. The concert was entirely cool and badass except for one part: his thank-you about half-way through. Now, I tend to think of James Hetfield as an awesome metal god and a badass. However, when he improvs apparently his inner dork begins to glow and we all definitely saw it through his leather vest. He started a call and repeat in the middle of one of the songs (I forget which) that began as simply a part of the song. Yet, this quickly devolved into him saying, nay, <em>chanting</em> things at the audience such as “Metallicuuuhhh,” “Metallicuuuhhh and Oriooonnn,” “Togetheratlast,” “Metallicafamily,” “Orion famuhlay,” “One big famuhlay.” (Those are attempted phoneticisms, not actual spellings.) Oh Jesus was it painful. Not only was he shedding some of his awesome in exchange for a dork hat, but in addition the crowd petered out after “Metcallicuuuhhh and Oriooonnn.” Oh well, the concert was so awesome taken as a whole. <strong>The Wrap</strong> While I didn’t see Barbara or Ellen at any of the other stages, I hear they did make more appearances that night and the next. They complement each other nicely. I think the festival was a total blast and a huge success, but I am not sure if it was planned to be annual. If it was, I think it definitely will and hope to see Barbara there again, but possibly not see Atlantic City. If that is the price I have to pay for Barbara and Metallica, then so be it.', 'Orion: Music + More', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '233-autosave', '', '', '2012-08-29 13:43:37', '2012-08-29 18:43:37', '', 233, 'http://www.slushie.me/251/233-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(299, 2, '2012-12-03 23:50:31', '2012-12-04 04:50:31', '<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/imkcages.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-283" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/imkcages-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="203" height="156" /></a>\r\n\r\nAt the conclusion of the Chiefs 27-21 victory over the Carolina Panthers, there must have been a bitter sweet feeling. In the wake of the death of Jovan Blecher a starting linebacker for the Chiefs, they endured a difficult contest against the Panthers and were able to snap their eight game losing streak.\r\nAccording to some analyst, however there is a bigger issue looming. Should the NFL have allowed the game to continue on as scheduled in light of these events? For the Chiefs players themselves the answer was yes, and after a moment of silence the Chiefs put out their best performance of the year. During a season where fans have died claiming the Chief’s ineptitude as the cause, it must have been nice for Chiefs fans watching the game today. A plane usually flying overhead to endorse the firing of GM Scott Pioli was absent. Chiefs fans usually decked out in black to protest the team’s struggles showed up in red.\r\n\r\nWhile Brady Quinn’s job in Kansas City maybe conclude at the end of this season, he deserves praise for his work today. Quinn threw for 201 yards on 23 attempts gaining an 83% completion rating; Quinn also threw two touchdowns. Jamaal Charles continues his recent resurgence today, gaining 127 yards on 27 carries.<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/156941966.0_standard_352.0.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-278" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/156941966.0_standard_352.0-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a>Regardless of the future for the Kansas City Chiefs, which may or may not involve the number one draft pick this year, the effort today shows a wonderful resilience and mental toughness about the team. It also shows that the world doesn’t always revolve around football and that there is a larger life outside of the game.', 'Chiefs get emotional win on Sunday', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '274-revision-19', '', '', '2012-12-03 23:50:31', '2012-12-04 04:50:31', '', 274, 'http://www.slushie.me/299/274-revision-19/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
