(456, 2, '2013-02-09 15:52:01', '2013-02-09 20:52:01', 'I have always really liked Valve. Gabe Newell always seemed pretty cool. I love Half-Life and and adore Portal. Yet, I have always pretty adamantly disliked Steam: it was a mediocre software distribution system on my Windows machine and barely functioned on my Mac. In the past couple of months, however, their awesomeness has been expanding.\n\n<strong>Steambox (Piston)</strong>\n\nTotally awesome. So many reasons. It would be optimized for Steam so it would run it smoothly and properly. Probably it would be way cheaper than the Xbox 720 (or Xbox 3 or whatever the kids are calling it these days) and the PS4/Orbis as it looks like it would run for $200, possibly $300. Even if it debuted at a higher price than the two, it would probably have a wide range of applications. It would work as a standard set-top box/HTPC set up with Steam''s Big Picture. It would run games at console graphics or better. It would have a full OS on it so it could be adjusted to run full-on desktop applications. Basically, and not to sound like a Valve fanboy, but it would actually revolutionize the home theater industry.  It would force major players to make things more powerful, open, and cheaper.\n\n<strong>Movies</strong><strong> &amp; New Games</strong>\n\nAt Dice 2013, Gabe Newell gave a few talks. One of these was a discussion with J. J. Abrams. Newell later explained that it was the publicized version of private talks that had been going on for a while. Basically they talked about the pros and cons of their respective mediums of story telling. Then they proposed that Abrams make a movie of Portal of Half Life. I like Half Life. I love Portal. PLEASE PLEASE MAKE A PORTAL MOVIE.\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="http://i3.kym-cdn.com/photos/images/newsfeed/000/264/241/9e9.gif" width="500" height="281" /></p>\nJust while I''m geeking out over this here is someone''s amazing mash-up of Iron Man and GLaDOS. If there was a movie of this, directed by Joss Whedon, every geek e<a href="http://24.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m7xb3jMMVm1r3xlxko1_500.png"><img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="http://24.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m7xb3jMMVm1r3xlxko1_500.png" width="398" height="750" /></a>\n\nIn less exciting and awesome and totally dork-gasmic news, they also talked about a collaborative video game. Frankly, they both of some of the best logo/intro/thingies: the Bad Robot running around in the grass and the creepy guy with a faucet in his head.\n\n<strong>New Steam</strong>\n\nAnd finally Newell was talking about freeing up the store fronts. Not just like Greenlight, but actually really opening things up. Allowing users to curate their own stores. It would also open it up to faster publication of awesome small games. Things would also get cheaper as it became more of a fluid ecosystem and there was more direct competition without regulation.', 'Valve Is Awesome', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '450-revision-5', '', '', '2013-02-09 15:52:01', '2013-02-09 20:52:01', '', 450, 'http://www.slushie.me/456/450-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
