(492, 2, '2013-02-27 21:48:12', '2013-02-28 02:48:12', '<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://oppostyle.com/modules//homeslider/images/a9d0ca600524d7e5d5a2a65ad0e30e1e.jpg"><img class="wp-image-495" alt="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/a9d0ca600524d7e5d5a2a65ad0e30e1e.jpg" width="877" height="390" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">I knew that the <a href="http://en.meizu.com/products/mx2-specifications.html" target="_blank">Meizu MX2</a> was a powerful, gorgeous phone. I recalled hearing something about the Oppo Find 5 around the time that the iPhone 5 rumor mills were really going full-steam last year. I do not remember that it was both attractive and possibly the most powerful phone on the entire market.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Bad</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Before I really get into this, allow me to say that the only downside I can tell (without a demo unit, *wink wink*) is the Oppo skin for Android. Flyme (Meizu''s Android skin) is a really nice, simplistic, and graphically pleasing overlay that keeps the best things about barebones android. Oppo''s, while not un-attractive or clunky like TouchWiz used to be, seems a little... off. It''s hard to describe what exactly is off, but I am just not a fan. Maybe it seems like it was designed for a 12-year old Belieber, but I dunno, not a fan.</p>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_493" align="aligncenter" width="782"]<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/find-5-features.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-493 " alt="Clouds? Shine? Designed with Beliebers in mind. Without a doubt." src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/find-5-features.jpg" width="782" height="469" /></a> I''ll leave it to you to decide on the UI. [<a href="http://oppostyle.com/index.php?id_product=9&amp;controller=product" target="_blank">source</a>][/caption]\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Now on to the best part: the parts. But where to begin? Let''s start on the inside, as I really am just a spec-junkie.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Inside</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">This phone is really just a computer that someone zapped into a really sexy Altoids tin. While quad-core and 1GHz+ has become the standard for flagship phones, I still can''t get over the fact that a tiny little object like that packs almost as much power as my twice-as-expensive, ten-times-as-big laptop exists. Well, this monster supersmartphone has a quad-core, 1.5GHz arm cortex serving as its little awesome brain. Mind you, this isn''t like other smartphones'' processors that have an integrated GPU, oh no, Oppo didn''t stop there. This phone has a discrete GPU. I''ll let that sink in. Granted, much of this power will probably be absorbed by the crazy-big screen it has, but that is still really useful for actual gaming. It also has 2GB of RAM which should definitely help with games. Again, while now standard, 2GB of RAM still kind of boggles my mind in a phone.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 is just packed with communications technologies and sensors. So much so I''mma just bullet this bitch (from least to most exciting, or in no particular order).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>GPS</li>\r\n	<li>GSM/EDGE</li>\r\n	<li>Ton of hi-speed 3G radios [no LTE :(]</li>\r\n	<li>Microphone</li>\r\n	<li>Digital Compass</li>\r\n	<li>Gyroscope</li>\r\n	<li>Bluetooth</li>\r\n	<li>NFC</li>\r\n	<li>Light Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Magnetic Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Proximity Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Wi-Fi Display/DLNA</li>\r\n	<li>Wi-Fi Direct</li>\r\n	<li>Gravity Sensor</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Did you read the last one? GRAVITY SENSOR. Ye gods, what purpose has this? Not going to explain Wi-Fi Display/Direct/DLNA as they are basically just a more open and versatile version of Apple''s AirPlay. The one thing that is strange is that it doesn''t have LTE. Monster specs and no LTE? Weird. It also ships with 16 or 32 GB of what the website calls ROM. Typically that stands for Read Only Memory, like really old CDs. I assume they mean regular flash storage, it would suck if you couldn''t save anything on your phone or change any settings or take pictures or anything that required any storage beyond RAM.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 also sports a crazy-big 2500mAh battery. The iPhone 5 has a 1200mAh battery and the Samsung Galaxy S3 has a 2100mAh battery. Still, it probably won''t have that great battery life due to the insane power and display it has.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/gsmarena_001.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-496" alt="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/gsmarena_001.jpg" width="580" height="343" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;"><strong>The Outside</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The case is a nice light silver metal for once. Metal all the way baby. Plastic phones suck and don''t feel as good in your hand. The camera is rather spectacular as well. 13MP rear and a front facing one. Not only does it take 13MP pictures with a 2.2 aperture,  but it has built in hardware support for special image processing, like Apple toted in the 4S and 5. It takes 1080p video at 120 FPS. What. The ad even proclaims that its five times faster than we can perceive. Oh well, the more the merrier. It also features a cool "Burst Mode" where it can take up to 5 photos per second for 20 seconds <del>almost like a lame video (link to Vine).</del></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 features a rather large speaker on the back and Apple-ripoff stock earbuds. Seriously people, stop copying Apple''s earbuds. They suck. Like bad.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Display</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">What the actual crap. The Find 5 has a 5-inch display with a 1080p screen. However, the resolution exceeds that of the Meizu and the iPhone 5 at 441 PPI. I can only, on the rare occasion discern a pixel on the Retina Displays. This display is crazy. Like almost no point to it crazy. But there is a point: it can be done.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Wrap Up</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">If you are a TL;DR person or just in a TL;DR mood, then feel free to just read the first and last paragraphs, jerk. Running Jelly Bean, this is almost without a doubt the most powerful phone on the market right now. However, it isn''t the best phone. Lacking some key features like LTE, expandable memory, and a good UI the Find 5 can''t be the top dog. It can still rank. But with a big price tag, it probably won''t be. If you want a good looking, powerful, light phone that is the Android equivalent of an iPhone, go for this one.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Two last things. I can''t help but think that the Find 5''s name is a publicity stunt. Sure it can be argued that it has a 5" display, but it seems more to me like it is trying to get some search results from "iPhone 5." I can''t resist. OPPO Find Style.<a href="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mbbxettdRA1rcdbkgo1_1280.gif"><img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mbbxettdRA1rcdbkgo1_1280.gif" width="600" height="720" /></a></p>', 'Only Dark Wizardry Could Jam This Much Into A Smartphone (Oppo Find 5)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'only-dark-wizardry-could-jam-this-much-into-a-smartphone-oppo-find-5', '', '', '2013-03-13 06:22:40', '2013-03-13 11:22:40', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=492', 0, 'post', '', 0),
