gin? Let''s start on the inside, as I really am just a spec-junkie.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Inside</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">This phone is really just a computer that someone zapped into a really sexy Altoids tin. While quad-core and 1GHz+ has become the standard for flagship phones, I still can''t get over the fact that a tiny little object like that packs almost as much power as my twice-as-expensive, ten-times-as-big laptop exists. Well, this monster supersmartphone has a quad-core, 1.5GHz arm cortex serving as its little awesome brain. Mind you, this isn''t like other smartphones'' processors that have an integrated GPU, oh no, Oppo didn''t stop there. This phone has a discrete GPU. I''ll let that sink in. Granted, much of this power will probably be absorbed by the crazy-big screen it has, but that is still really useful for actual gaming. It also has 2GB of RAM which should definitely help with games. Again, while now standard, 2GB of RAM still kind of boggles my mind in a phone.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 is just packed with communications technologies and sensors. So much so I''mma just bullet this bitch (from least to most exciting, or in no particular order).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style="text-align: left;">\r\n	<li><span style="line-height: 14px;">GPS</span></li>\r\n	<li>GSM/EDGE</li>\r\n	<li>Ton of hi-speed 3G radios [no LTE :(]</li>\r\n	<li>Microphone</li>\r\n	<li>Digital Compass</li>\r\n	<li>Gyroscope</li>\r\n	<li>Bluetooth</li>\r\n	<li>NFC</li>\r\n	<li>Light Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Magnetic Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Proximity Sensor</li>\r\n	<li>Wi-Fi Display/DLNA</li>\r\n	<li>Wi-Fi Direct</li>\r\n	<li>Gravity Sensor</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;">Did you read the last one? GRAVITY SENSOR. Ye gods, what purpose has this? Not going to explain Wi-Fi Display/Direct/DLNA as they are basically just a more open and versatile version of Apple''s AirPlay. The one thing that is strange is that it doesn''t have LTE. Monster specs and no LTE? Weird. It also ships with 16 or 32 GB of what the website calls ROM. Typically that stands for Read Only Memory, like really old CDs. I assume they mean regular flash storage, it would suck if you couldn''t save anything on your phone or change any settings or take pictures or anything that required any storage beyond RAM.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 also sports a crazy-big 2500mAh battery. The iPhone 5 has a 1200mAh battery and the Samsung Galaxy S3 has a 2100mAh battery. Still, it probably won''t have that great battery life due to the insane power and display it has.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/gsmarena_001.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-496" alt="" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/gsmarena_001.jpg" width="580" height="343" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;"><strong>The Outside</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;">The case is a nice light silver metal for once. Metal all the way baby. Plastic phones suck and don''t feel as good in your hand. The camera is rathe spectacular as well. 13MP rear and a front facing one. Not only does it take 13MP pictures with a 2.2 aperture,  but it has built in hardware support for special image processing, like Apple toted in the 4S and 5. It takes 1080p video at 120 FPS. What. The ad even proclaims that its five times faster than we can perceive. Oh well, the more the merrier. It also features a cool "Burst Mode" where it can take up to 5 photos per second for 20 seconds <del>almost like a lame video (link to Vine).</del> </span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Find 5 features a rather large speaker on the back and Apple-ripoff stock earbuds. Seriously people, stop copying Apple''s earbuds. They suck. Like bad.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Display</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">What the actual crap. The Find 5 has a 5-inch display with a 1080p screen. However, the resolution exceeds that of the Meizu and the iPhone 5 at 441 PPI. I can only, on the rare occasion discern a pixel on the Retina Displays. This display is crazy. Like almost no point to it crazy. But there is a point: it can be done.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>The Wrap Up</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">If you are a TL;DR person or just in a TL;DR mood, then feel free to just read the first and last paragraphs, jerk. Running Jelly Bean, this is almost without a doubt the most powerful phone on the market right now. However, it isn''t the best phone. Lacking some key features like LTE, expandable memory, and a good UI the Find 5 can''t be the top dog. It can still rank. But with a big price tag, it probably won''t be. If you want a good looking, powerful, light phone that is the Android equivalent of an iPhone, go for this one.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Two last things. I can''t help but think that the Find 5''s name is a publicity stunt. Sure it can be argued that it has a 5" display, but it seems more to me like it is trying to get some search results from "iPhone 5." I can''t resist. OPPO Find Style.<a href="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mbbxettdRA1rcdbkgo1_1280.gif"><img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mbbxettdRA1rcdbkgo1_1280.gif" width="600" height="720" /></a></p>', 'Only Dark Wizardry Could Jam This Much Into A Smartphone (Oppo Find 5)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '492-revision-6', '', '', '2013-02-27 21:53:20', '2013-02-28 02:53:20', '', 492, 'http://www.slushie.me/502/492-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(518, 9, '2013-05-01 20:34:28', '2013-05-02 01:34:28', '<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Tom-Cruise-Oblivion-HD-Wallpaper_Vvallpaper.Net_.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-522" alt="Oblivion Banner Image" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Tom-Cruise-Oblivion-HD-Wallpaper_Vvallpaper.Net_.jpg" width="1600" height="1000" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis movie represents the tenuous connection between Hollywood and any kind of scientific fact that may exist.\r\n\r\nThe first noticeable of the VERY few possible redeeming qualities, for some people, may be Tom Cruise’s blatantly ridiculous face.  Through what can only be assumed to be a mixture of Scientological magic and utterly phenomenal make-up artists, he still looks like a much younger (and slightly less creepy) Tom Cruise.\r\n\r\nDespite the perceived attractiveness of some of these characters, Tom Cruise not being the only visually pleasurable member of the cast, caring even a little about the simply moronic decisions the writers of this movie chose would be pushing the powers of empathy.\r\n\r\nThe basic plot runs as follows: we find Jack Harper and Victoria in a post-apocalyptic world. These two are dedicated to fixing the drones that protect the giant fusion engines that run by sucking the Oceans into what looks like a giant, flying, silver oil rig.\r\n\r\nThese drones protect the giant fusion reactors from what has been termed the “scavengers”, the beings responsible for the apocalypse. After these “Scavs” attacked Earth, the world decided that nukes would be the best option, leaving the planet a radiated wasteland.\r\n\r\nHumanity decided it’d be best if they headed off to Titan, a moon of (I want to say Saturn?), leaving a giant black obelisk floating over the Earth, called the Tet, which serves as the control center for the drones and for the giant fusion engines.\r\n\r\nAs anyone who has taken the time out of their otherwise important day to watch the trailer can see, everything is not as it seems.\r\n\r\nAfter an annoyingly long intro sequence and some flashbacks to a pre-apocalyptic New York street and building that Jack Harper couldn’t possibly remember, due to a mandatory memory wipe, the movie continues at an agonizing pace.\r\n\r\nBut, before I continue, just a word on the idea of a memory wipe. This blatantly silly piece of writing was placed in there with little to no justification (something about keeping the integrity of the mission intact, or some equally useless explanation), and serves as a pretty accurate symbol for how forced and unintelligent so much of his plot ends up being.\r\n\r\nNow, back on point. I can tell you now that not expecting all the plot twists that we all pretty much knew were going to happen eventually, do not make them any better.  Instead the audience ends up with a “Oh. Well. Ok. That was a pretty dumb sequence of events.” moment, instead of the earth shattering, mind-blowing scene that the writers seemed to be going for.\r\n\r\nIt seems the more the movie tries to act on its audiences nostalgia and emotions, the more comical it becomes. But as comical as these scenes sometimes are, they are far more likely to be agonizingly dumb.\r\n\r\nI think the absolute best way to describe how miserable this movie is would be to say that not even Morgan Freeman could make this worth watching. I’m going to let that sink in. Not even Morgan Freeman, who’s voice can make pretty much any phrase in any language the epitome of poetry, could make this movie worth watching.\r\n\r\nAbout a third of the way through the movie, it becomes more of a miserable compilation of infuriatingly obvious clichés that pretty much continue through the end of the movie, despite some oh so stupid twists.\r\n\r\nIf you enjoy moderately good CGI, despite a backdrop of cruelly bad movie making, then you may be able to just barely sit through this movie without cringing. But I doubt it.\r\n\r\nSomething about the so-bad-they’re-not-even-corny one liners make this movie stop just short of so-good-it’s-bad and gets stuck in just-awful.\r\n\r\nI have sat through inhumanly complicated biology lectures (though I feel less awful about those, since at least I was forced to sit through them) at some colleges, and even those didn’t feel like they lasted as long as the infinites of pain that this movie inflicts on your sensibilities.\r\n\r\nPlease, for the sake of all things good in this world, do not waste your hard earned money on the worst movie I’ve seen this year.', 'Oblivion: A Review', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'oblivion-a-review', '', '', '2013-05-01 20:37:53', '2013-05-02 01:37:53', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=518', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(520, 9, '2013-05-01 20:24:39', '2013-05-02 01:24:39', 'Lying between Falls Road and Greenspring is the Park School. Private, expensive, and to some degree exclusive, the Park school represents a much larger population of private schools in America.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nClassically, schools like these have only been attended by the rich, or near rich, but one policy introduced in a few cities could let parents choose to send their kids to the Parks School.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nVouchers, known by advocates as School Choice, are traditionally checks sent to private or charter schools, which allow poorer students to attend more expensive institutions, like the Park School.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nFor some, this may seem like the answer to a flawed educational system. It gives parents the ability to choose where their child should go, instead of being forced into sending them to their district public school.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nStrangely, this seemingly simple concept has become one of the most divisive issues in the modern educational debate.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n“Many people are concerned that vouchers run afoul of the church-state separation or that they threaten the public education system.” Said Gabriel Aaronson, a school choice advocate who recently left his job as the Public Policy Fellow for the Orthodox Union, in an email interview earlier this week.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOne of the majorly controversial points of vouchers, as Aaronson mentions, is their connection with the first amendment and the separation of church and state. This separation becomes an issue because, theoretically, voucher money could go to a religious school.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThis particular issue was brought to court in the case Zelman v Simmons Harris, which ultimately ruled in favor vouchers, given certain caveats. This includes parents having the choice between religious and non-religious schools, and money to other educational options, such as charter, or magnet schools like City.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe idea of vouchers threatening, or at least potentially harming the school system is a popular one among voucher critics.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n“The idea I think is to build up the schools, and I’m not sure the voucher system does that.” Said Sedrick Smith, the Union representative for City and an IB world and MYP humanities teacher.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n“We’re passing the buck with the voucher system. We’re taking a few kids out and giving them the opportunity to go to these schools, but what we really need to do is recreate the schools.”\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOn this point, Aaronson and other advocates partially agree. “[Vouchers] are simply an important component of comprehensive education reform”, said Aaronson.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nHowever, because it does not deal with what Mr. Smith considers he underlying reasons for poor education, does that mean that vouchers are entirely ineffective?\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIn this case, some more specific, statistical evidence may be helpful.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Oblivion: A Review', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '518-revision-2', '', '', '2013-05-01 20:24:39', '2013-05-02 01:24:39', '', 518, 'http://www.slushie.me/520/518-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
