(538, 2, '2013-05-15 15:55:24', '2013-05-15 20:55:24', 'Almost any even mildly action-y movie and its trailer that you watch now has that same ‘whooomp’ sound in it somewhere. Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. Pacific Rim. Oblivion. Iron Man 3. It’s a deep throb of bass. I first heard this in Inception, way back in the yesteryear of 2010. It was cool. It was a big sound that did exactly what the creators wanted it to do: it impressed you; it made you feel like there was something that was impending; it was urgent and it was massive. For a couple months afterwards wherever you heard that sound, you thought Inception. Now it has simply become a staple of making anything seem monumental, almost like lens flares in a J. J. Abrams movie. Speaking of which, it pops up a couple times in the new Star Trek.\n\nAt the same time that this was gaining ground in the movie industry, something similar was happening to popular music. Dubstep has been around for quite a while, but has only really come to any prominence or mainstream popularity in the United States. However, almost any electronic music that feels frenetic with a heavy bassline has been loosely labeled as ''dubstep.'' Regardless of the accuracy of the term, the new trend of bass in popular music is real and most easily labeled dubstep, so at the risk of sounding ignorant I''ll use that from now on. Dubstep has become famous for the ''wub'' sound of heavy swooping bass interlaced with higher pitches.\n\nThere is something about the sound of the soaring bass that is extremely popular right now, why it became popular I know not. Maybe personal audio has better bass than it used to? Maybe only the whippersnappers can hear it? Who knows, but it''s everywhere. My argument is that there is no way that the whooomp trend in movies and the popularity of dubstep are unrelated. Dubstep started getting popular in the States in 2009, right before Inception and Skrillex. Both acts popularized what we are now familiar with.\n\nThe problem we now face is that this sound is no longer special in movies. Much as the zombie romance fad went from all the craze to being way over done, whooomp sound effects in movies are starting to be overused. Before they become too cliché and obvious that they are annoying or dated in 10-15 years, the use should be toned down. Don''t use them in every movie. Save it up for once at the end or when it really matters. If we don''t kids in twenty years will hear that noise and know with complete certainty that the movie came out between 2010 and 2015.', 'Of Inception and Dubstep', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '531-revision-7', '', '', '2013-05-15 15:55:24', '2013-05-15 20:55:24', '', 531, 'http://www.slushie.me/538/531-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
