(563, 8, '2013-05-16 19:39:51', '2013-05-17 00:39:51', 'If you thought this was going to be a movie review you would be dead wrong. Although I will get out of the way now that I really enjoyed the movie, this is not about the movie. The soundtrack alone of The Great Gatsby could easily give it a solid 6/10 rating from me. While some people say the movie wasn''t over the top enough to match Fitzgerald''s book, I would tell them to listen to A Little Party Never Killed Nobody. The mix of vocals from the Black Eyed Peas and other artist mixed with the near dubstep sections does an excellent job of showing the over the top nature of one of Jay Gatsby''s parties. I would argue however that Baz Luhrmann''s focus in this film was not on the party nature of the 1920s, but on the emotions characters feel in The Great Gatsby.\n\nKill and Run by Sia, Over The Love by Florence &amp; The Machine, and arguably the best song of the movie Young and Beautiful by Lana Del Rey, all do an excellent job of bringing the audience into the minds and hearts of Nick, Daisy, Jordan, and Gatsby. These songs in particular could easily bring the audience to tears as they view the failed romance of Daisy and Gatsby.\n\nYes the movie had its share of problems, but the goods definitely outweighed the bads. The Hollywood debut of Amitabh Bachchan after a long successful career in Bollywood is totally welcome. The creative trimming of the movie was also fine when you think of the movie as a separate entity from the book. The funeral scene was a little suspect but other than that I can''t think of much I have to knock this movie on.\n\nSo yes this did somewhat turn into a review (kind of). However, I hope that everyone at least gives one or two of these songs a look on iTunes because they seriously are the real deal.', 'The Great Gatsby Soundtrack was good and if you don''t think so get out!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '561-revision', '', '', '2013-05-16 19:39:51', '2013-05-17 00:39:51', '', 