(598, 13, '2013-07-20 20:24:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Violence is synonymous as well as a staple of Video Games, this we all know.  But the new game industry is overflowing with new things as a side dish with violence.  With Team Fortress 2, we added an in-game haberdashery, and the Gamer was pleased.  So, with this game being out for 6 years, we need a replacement right? Loadout might just be that replacement... when it''s finished.  The game is currently in Alpha, and with a Steam account, one can purchase their way into the open Alpha.  With 10 dollars laying around, I purchased it thinking "This could be swell!" and... Well you''ll see.\n\nThe game is an online shooter, where the goal is to kill other people with personally crafted weapons.  Sounds fun right? The problem is, the guns aren''t what you expect them to be.  A gun that electrocutes your enemies with shotgun-style rockets should basically cheat the system right? Balancing issues make it so when electricity is added, or incendiary bullets, the weapon''s core damage is considerably lessened.  Makes sense, right? The after-burn/shock damage isn''t that great. In fact, it just sucks.\n\nInstead of drops, like Team Fortress, you earn in-game cash called Spacebucks (why? I''m not sure. You''re not in space as far as I can tell) in which you can buy new pants... or buy no pants.  Yeah, you have to pay money to be naked. I see where it makes sense from a gameplay standpoint, because being naked is hilarious (complete with rather large, blurred out genitalia), so it should be hard to unlock. However, it makes no sense that you have to pay money to remove your pants entirely.\n\nThe weapon creation is well done, and it makes you feel like your weapon was a labor of love.  The testing area is also good, as it gives you standing still bots that will help you get a good idea of how strong a direct hit is, and bots running around that show you how accurate the gun is.  It''s really hard to make a weapon that''s a good anything though.  I''d seen gameplay from when the game was newer, and from what I gather, the weapons are much more overpowered.  The problem with all of this is that the devs have two options: Either make the weapons really overpowered, which falls in to the game design principle that the most overpowered anything will be used no matter what.  Or, make the weapons lower in power and balanced, but suddenly, weapons that physically make sense to blow everything up, don''t.  So the game feels really awkward and unfair, even though everyone''s more or less on the same level.\n\nThere''s a lot more to write about, but a lot will change.  I''m right now explaining how the Alpha is the game as of right now.  So what you can do, is pay 10 dollars and get a game that will probably get a lot better.  This game gets a 5/10 from me, it''s all there, but it doesn''t feel right.  The game''s kind of clunky, the controls are okay...', 'More Gun - LOADOUT(Alpha) Review', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-20 20:24:51', '2013-07-21 01:24:51', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=598', 0, 'post', '', 0),
