(600, 13, '2013-07-22 20:49:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'So we''ve all heard about it.  The dastardly NSA and their PRISM, spying on us.  Well, what does that even mean?\r\n\r\nLet''s start with CISPA.\r\n\r\nThe Cyber Intelligence Sharing Protection Act is a bill that''s been around Congress for a while now.  Long story short, it basically says that the government will have access to anything you browse or download, simply by filling out a small form, and knowing the IP Address.  It sounds evil right? What they''re looking for here is two things: Piracy (the age old battle between Hollywood and the User) and potentially threatening persons.  This bill obviously arose after the Boston Marathon Bombings, as after a tragedy, the Government likes to increase somewhere where they feel they flawed, in this case Telecommunications and Network surveillance. So it makes sense to reintroduce these things right?  Well, look at it this way.  There''s around 300 Million people in the United States.  Red-Flagged phrases can be used to find certain people, but it isn''t stopping anyone from doing bad things.  There are other ways of communication, right? It''s like telling a child he can''t, say, play with dolls. That child will look at their dolls, get upset, and then look over at their box of toys and start anew with a different toy. The process continues, but the problem is, the child will always find a way to entertain themselves.  The same could happen with terrorists.  After 9/11, airport security skyrocketed. Let''s just say for a moment, that airport security was 100% effective at what it was trying to do, and it was literally impossible for a terrorist to do anything involving a plane. They could sit around and go "Well, we can''t do anything with a plane, what''s next?" And in this case, bombing a marathon was the next big thing that stuck.  So what do we do there? We find out that they used the internet to communicate and research bomb making. You could say the obvious wide-angled solution is to go and survey internet and phones, and you wouldn''t be barking up the wrong tree. If you aren''t doing anything wrong, what''s to worry about?\r\n\r\nA lot.  You see, people can''t always determine what''s wrong or right.  For example, a Movie Critic might say that a certain movie is bad.  Another might say it''s a good movie.  It''s all objective.  And certainly there are things that we can denote as being actually bad, or at least, what society as a whole has deemed bad (things like Murder and Stealing).  But what if someone killed your family, and you wanted to get revenge? Or someone destroyed your car, and you thought you''d take something to, in your eyes, pay them back? There''s a lot of things you can say are good and bad, and there''s always exceptions.', 'NSA Rant (Part 1)', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'nsa_', '', '', '2013-07-22 20:49:11', '2013-07-23 01:49:11', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=600', 0, 'post', '', 0),
