(618, 2, '2013-07-10 14:11:28', '2013-07-10 19:11:28', 'It’s bad enough that we architects are <strong>craven, boot-licking toadies</strong> whenever a dollar-bill is so much as waved coquettishly – like a perfumed hankie! – in front of our eyes. But once we lick the boot, can we not at least stand up and say truthfully whether or not it tastes like shit? Has our profession abdicated so much of our judgment that we can’t tell the difference between “functional” and “bad”? <strong>Have we lost the artistic skill to do better?</strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_589" align="alignnone" width="625"]<a href="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/2810-Sisson-Street.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-589" alt="Department of Public Works Building at 2810 Sission Street" src="http://www.slushie.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/2810-Sisson-Street-1024x717.jpg" width="625" height="437" /></a> Modern Architecture -- and its Stupidification[/caption]\r\n\r\nNot surprisingly, this almost-final straw is yet another bad fix-it-up visited upon a poor, defenseless building: a modest modernist shed at 2810 Sission Street, Baltimore, Maryland. For years, this building has served the waste management activities of Baltimore’s Department of Public Works, and perhaps its original function was the same. Whatever its origin, this<strong> Symphony in Stacked Bond</strong> persevered for years as a remnant of a time when architects actually stood for something: well-scaled public entrance; clerestory windows; contrasting block and brick walls; and large glass curtain-wall overlooking the movement of crap back and forth. Best was the balance between the building’s horizontality (Modern!) and its simplicity (even more Modern!), a balance which lies at the heart of so many great buildings by Wright, Mies, and their devoted minions.\r\n\r\nBut:<b> A <span style="text-decoration: underline">crown molding</span> on the damn thing?!?  Really?!?</b>\r\n\r\nToo many recent renovations have junked up what few examples of decent architecture we have left from the ‘50’s and ‘60’s. They’re tearing down <a href="http://www.architectmagazine.com/architecture/brutalist-theater-in-baltimore-faces-demolition.aspx" target="_blank">Johansen’s Mechanic Theater</a>. <a href="http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-10-09/features/9910090286_1_oheb-shalom-temple-oheb-congregation" target="_blank">Gropius’s Oheb Shalom</a> is now “user friendly.” And someone slapped a bizarre sloped shed roof on North Avenue’s KAGRO building. Dumb!\r\n\r\nWho''s at fault? Must be us, the architects, as a profession: <strong><em>We''re</em> getting dumber</strong>.', 'Who Put the Diaper on My Modern Architecture?!?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '590-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-07-10 14:11:28', '2013-07-10 19:11:28', '', 590, 'http://www.slushie.me/618/590-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
