(621, 2, '2011-11-14 22:20:46', '2011-11-15 03:20:46', '<em>by </em><strong>Tucker Chapin</strong><img title="iCloud" alt="" src="http://cache.gizmodo.com/assets/images/4/2011/11/xlarge_ff035225dac4bac7c0235b2e03b42249.png" width="640" height="360" />\r\n\r\nBoth Google Music and iCloud have been announced for a while, but only now are they beginning to <em>get real. </em>Google Music launched a while ago, but as an invite-only beta testing service. The premise of GMusic, at least this is how the beta works, is to upload all (yes, all million bajillion of them) of your music library to the Google Music servers for storage. Once this is done, and it takes a looong time since each song is <em>at leas</em><em>t </em>3MB, you can play your music back with their Android app, iOS webapp, or standard website. While I can''t speak for the Android app (though I hear it is similar), the webapp and standard site are good, but have a lot of room for improvement as they are both still clunky, unresponsive and slow. iCloud was announced at Apple''s WWDC earlier this year and has been open to developers for a bit, but, as of today, is now open to the public as well. It will cost you a delightfully tiny $25 a year for any and all music you can throw at it. Instead of uploading all of your music, it scans your library and basically tells Apple''s servers "Hey, this dude has this track, put this in his file." "Okay." <em>Yes that''s how servers talk, now you know. Your welcome.</em> This means it takes minutes rather than days and gives you higher fidelity and better quality (probably) audio than you already had. PLUS it syncs this across all of your iOS devices wirelessly. Read on pas the break for elaboration and schtuph.\r\n\r\n<img title="More..." alt="" src="https://tuckerwchapindotwordpressdotcom.wordpress.com/wp-includes/js/tinymce/plugins/wordpress/img/trans.gif" /><strong>iCloud</strong><img title="iCloud2" alt="" src="http://fastcache.gawkerassets.com/assets/images/4/2011/11/839da877a7d15f39a597fad986712ef6.jpg" width="640" height="360" />\r\n\r\nI will quickly reiterate the process I brieflydescribed before. iCloud scans your library and creates a database of what you have and links this to your account. Any song you have that iTunes sells won''t need to be uploaded, as Apple automatically upgrades yours to higher (probably) quality, 256kbps AAC DRM-free. Anything you do have, and this will be a small amount, iCloud will upload and store for use by your account. This means that anything you have that Apple has is automatically upgrade to higher quality and anything you dont can be accessed along side that and anywhere in the world you get internet.[<a title="Gizmodo" href="http://gizmodo.com/5859316/itunes-match-is-live-at-long-last" target="_blank">Gizmodo</a>]\r\n\r\niCloud debuted today and you have to download the latest version of iTunes to use it. Download that and follow the instructions. If you have issues, I''m sure Google would be <em>glad </em>to help you out. [<a title="Gizmodo" href="http://gizmodo.com/5859461/everything-you-need-to-know-about-using-itunes-match/gallery/1" target="_blank">Gizmodo</a>]\r\n\r\nThe main issue with iCloud is also its greatest benefit. Seeing as how it automatically syncs your music across your devices, if your harddrive fails all of your music can be re-downloaded without a hitch. No probskis. The issue is that if you just want to listen to a song quickly and just stream, <em>not </em>download, it you can''t do so. It automatically downloads the music you listen to. Streaming may be added later, but who knows. The only way to stream is if your device is full, then it will simply stream the music and not download.\r\n\r\nYou are limited to 10 devices total and 25k songs. The device limit might be constraining for some, but I highly doubt that the song limit will be too troublesome for most people.\r\n\r\n<strong>Google Music</strong>\r\n\r\nBesides the arduous process of uploading your <em>entire </em>library, Google Music Beta has been pretty decent. After you have uploaded you entire library, subsequent uploads are a non-issue. The interface is currently the biggest issue. They will have to fix that and probably will announce some new apps, redesigns, or something of the sorts at their event on Wednesday that is supposedly addressing Google Music. Along with that, the even is rumored to fix the other issue preventing GMusic from truly taking on Cupertino: no store.\r\n<div><dl id=""><dt><a href="http://fastcache.gawkerassets.com/assets/images/4/2011/11/aaa0b2b2aaf986fa3be8a13738bd8ed1.jpg"><img title="Google Music Store" alt="" src="http://fastcache.gawkerassets.com/assets/images/4/2011/11/aaa0b2b2aaf986fa3be8a13738bd8ed1.jpg" width="640" height="360" /></a></dt><dd>Possibly what the Google Music Store looks like.</dd></dl></div>\r\nGoogle Music has no directly affiliated, built-in, or convenient store. Google probably assumes you are using either Amazon or iTunes, as most of us are. It has been no issue, but will never allow them to take iTunes on directly as that is the main reason people use iTunes: the store. [<a title="Gizmodo" href="http://gizmodo.com/5859504/google-music-store-screen-shots-surface-ahead-of-november-16-announcement" target="_blank">Gizmodo</a>]\r\n\r\nOther than those two issues, Google is doing pretty damn well with its Music venture when compared to the fates of Buzz, Wave and Plus (probably.). And we are just at the beta stage. Google Music currently allows you infinite devices and 20k songs. Again, not really a super big issue for most.\r\n\r\nWhich one are you?', 'Cloud Music Special: Google and Apple', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cloud-music-special-google-and-apple', '', '', '2013-10-21 19:49:21', '2013-10-22 00:49:21', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=621', 0, 'post', '', 0),
