(638, 2, '2011-11-12 23:31:57', '2011-11-13 04:31:57', '<em>by </em><strong>Tucker Chapin</strong>\r\n\r\nThere has been a lot of ruckus about the next gen. mobile processors. The prediction is of course faster, but also more cores. Quad-cores. We are really starting to hit the territory where the line between mobile and desktop processors is blurred. 1.5 Ghz has already been hit by dual cores and 2.1 has been hit by single cores of ARM cortex processors (the mobile variety). The Intel Atom series isn''t a whole lot different from the power of the dual core variety (granted that there are still a bunch of differences, but not in power). Anyhoo, the Tegra 3 (codename Kal-El) and the next gen. TI processors seem to be the ones that will be the first quad-core mobile processors on the market. Furthermore, the HTC Edge appears to be the front runner of devices to first receive this glory chip. Also appears to have Beats Audio and 4G, but with 4G becoming more and more ubiquitous and standard, it will need more than just those two qualities to be the next flagship. [<a title="Engadget" href="http://www.engadget.com/2011/11/07/htc-edge-may-be-the-first-quad-core-smartphone-to-market/?utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=pulsenews" target="_blank">Engadget</a>]', 'Who Will Be First to Quad-Core Mobility?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'who-will-be-first-to-quad-core-mobility', '', '', '2013-10-21 21:05:05', '2013-10-22 02:05:05', '', 0, 'http://www.slushie.me/?p=638', 0, 'post', '', 0),
